data.title: Great staff!
data.content: I had traveled by the sign at the entrance to the Anne Kobe Nature Center several times, and when my children said they wanted to take a trip to the Hollywood/Ft. Lauderdale area I knew what would be on the itinerary! Several months in advance I arranged for a guided tour of the facility and a boat ride around the mangroves.Catherine was waiting for us to show off the facility, play an interesting short film, and display and explain interesting aquatic animals in their water tank. There was plenty of seating and informative displays. She was very knowledgeable and answered everyone's questions. Captain Al was standing by to take us on an interesting ride around the mangroves. We learned about the different types of mangroves and spotted Ibis, Osprey, and a water iguana.  A good time had by all...group included 7 adults and 5 children! Next time we will look at the exhibit ahll more carefully and climb the outlook tower.

data.title: Rocky Terrain on Trails
data.content: On vacation we enjoy walking every morning, and wanted something different than walking the beach or the boardwalk, so we came here. Very happy to see Florida residents felt it was important in the 1970’s to preserve a little nature so close to its popular beaches. It has a very nice small education center, with a couple of walkouts to the water and a tower you can walk up or take an elevator up to the top. We also took the the 2 mile trail under the highway near the drawbridge, very poorly marked as far to which trail to take to stay on the looped trail.  The trail is very rocky and paved partially with cement, most likely to prevent erosion as the mangroves and water come right up to the trail during high tide. It was a nice January nature walk, not too much to see. We did however see a Yellow Crested Heron perched in the mangroves. I guess most locals know where to go, but if you are a visitor, you will be guessing as to where to turn on the 2 mile trail. This didn’t knock our socks off,  bus was free, educational and good exercise.

data.title: Just what we needed
data.content: We are in town for our Godson's baptism. Mom and baby wanted to get out of the house for a bit and we were looking to see just a bit more of Florida's natural beauty. This place was PERFECT. It is stroller friendly, including an elevator to the observation deck. The paths are easy and well-maintained. We saw lots of lizards, colorful birds, crabs, butterflies and even a family of raccoons. There are a few trails, they are not terribly long. So, if you're looking for a day of full immersion into wildlife, you might want to keep looking, but if you just want an hour or two to escape and relax without trading flip flops for hiking boots, this is what you want. Across the main road outside of the nature center area is a park that I am told you can rent canoes at, go biking and even fish. We didn't go over to this side, but this will probably add more to you experience if you can add it to your day.

data.title: An Aquarium and a View
data.content: The boat has been out of service for a very long time and we were told they are building new one. A work crew had activated the fire alarm so we couldn’t go into the Mangrove building until it was re-set. We had to prod answers out of the two staff outside ( engaged in their iPhones) as to where we could access a building to escape from the heat. We were told “ there’s just an aquarium”. We had a 4 1/2 year old who is extremely excited about all kinds of nature.Is this the best they could offer when the main building is “temporarily closed” for what? Maybe it’s lack of funding but more than anything else we experienced “ lack of enthusiasm “. Their turtle release program is very popular and fully booked through the summer.An elevator takes you to the top of the lookout and the view over the mangroves with the ocean in the distance is very nice.

data.title: Enjoyable, but boat captain retired
data.content: We (two adults who enjoy nature) enjoyed our time at the nature center. We  telephoned ahead and thus knew that there would be no pontoon boat ride. We were told the captain had retired recently. Perhaps he will be replaced; but either call ahead or make your trip assuming you'll be walking, not floating (unless you venture out in a kayak or canoe).The view from the observation tower was impressive. (One of us climbed the stairs; the other used the elevator.)A printed guide we were loaned at the nature center, which gives information based on numbered points along a boardwalk, alerted us to the presence of small pufferfish we saw when we looked closely. Our timing was wrong and thus we saw no birds, which are more likely in early morning and later in the afternoon than we were there.We also saw a big, green insect I'll imprecisely call a dragonfly — and a pretty little butterfly.We took a lunch break offsite between our walks on two boardwalks at the nature center.  Lunch was at a stand near a beach a short drive from the nature center. (We were allowed entry to the parking lot without paying the beach fee — perhaps because someone from the nature center telephoned the attendant, although perhaps all we needed to do was politely tell the attendant we only wanted to have lunch, not use the beach.)Artwork was displayed in a nature center building, as were turtle shells and other items one might expect in a nature center. Admission to the exhibits cost only $1.

data.title: Fabulous on a hot day
data.content: Be sure to do the little movie BEFORE you walk, then explore the exhibits. That way you have a better idea what you are seeing and hearing. We went during low tide and did not know the loud clicking and popping was SHRIMP. We kept looking into the trees because we thought it was birds! The first thing should be a trip up the high tower and yes they have an elevator, greatly appreciated by those of us in wheelchairs! You gat a fantastic view. Watch out for the little crabs as you walk the boardwalk. Two shorter walks will take you out to observation points on the lakes and you can sit and watch the ospreys search for fish. There is a longer third walk if you have time which will offer even more expansive views. We were there on a Monday morning so it was very quiet. Cool and almost mysterious as you wend through the mangroves listening to the birds.

data.title: Not a good place to observe wildlife.
data.content: I have visited the Anne Kolb Nature Centre on numerous occasions and have to say that I agree it is a very peaceful and quiet place.  Quiet because it is devoid of any noticeabe life! I used to think that was because I visited at the wrong time of year but having just returned after a late summer visit, I know that not to be the case. It is not the place to see wildlife apart from the occasional Ahningha and distant Osprey, I have yet to see anything remotely deserving of the title "Nature Centre". You may be lucky and see a crab amongst the mangroves but for wildlife, a visit to the nearby John U Lloyd park would be far more rewarding and even West Lake Park almost opposite has far more wildlife, particularly birds (especially in the early morning).  The viewing Tower is a weird structure and doesn't give you a view of anything and is an example of public spending at its most wasteful. All in all it's a nice  park but devoid of life. There is a review that talks of an indoor Nature Centre and a paved path down to the water, isn't this in itself a contradiction?I have no issue whatsoever with calling it the Anne Kolb Park because it is beautiful place, but a nature Centre it ain't.

data.title: a relaxing kayaking experience for any-level kayaker
data.content: The Anne Kolb Nature Center is beautifully maintained both inside and out. We enjoyed a relaxing day kayaking up and down the waterways. We were asked not to go out into the lake because there had been incidents of inexperienced kayakers having difficulties. While we were out, we observed some  college-age boaters doing exactly that!There was fascinating life among the mangrove, lots of crabs and we enjoyed it, but the directed, limited loop of travel  is better for younger or the inexperienced kayaker.

data.content: Across the street from the main park is a very rustic trail. Walking on the trail takes one away from the sights and sounds of urban sprawl. It takes about an hour to walk the trail. data.title: Best kept park in Broward, possible S. Florida
data.content: This place is wonderful for those naturlist that truly enjoy learning about the natural environment.  This one specializes in mangroves.   I learned so much that I didn't know about mangroves.  The views from the observation tower where awesome.  The boat tour was well worth the cost and the captain was very informative.  Saw many live birds and critters.  All the trails are worth the walk.  I would advise folks that the map you get from the vistor center is not to scale, look at the one on the trail instead.  BUG SPRAY IS A MUST.  The biting gnats are ferocious.  Bring something with Deet in it, 40% is good.  They mostly come out at low tide or later in the day I think, but don't quote me.  They stick to the dense mangrove areas but not to bad once you get out to the look outs or on the boat tour.  They don't leave a mark or itch, just painful as anything I have ever encountered in nature.This place is so well maintained.  I have seen many State parks so run down from having small budgets, but this place is a county park and must have some secret funding.  I am an architect and I can tell they take good care of their property and equipment.Enjoy.  Will be back to go canoeing since we didn't get a chance these first two trips here.NO PETS ALLOWED, SORRY.

value.text: explain the bio-systems that are unique to southern Florida

data.title: Good fun for a rainy day -- or a sunny one!
data.content: The Ann Kolb Nature Park is a lovely way to add a little depth to a visit to the beaches of southern Florida.  Its indoor exhibits are good for a rainy day, or for the intense hot hours between lunch and late afternoon.  The walking trails and boat tours explain the bio-systems that are unique to southern Florida.  It's a birdwatcher's paradise.  Plenty of parking, but it's also an easy bike-ride from almost anywhere in Hollywood.

data.content: Friendly staff!  When we arrived, we passed by a staff member who was gave us a warm welcome. We said sure because we had never been there before and we though that it would be a good idea to start with something structured.  Captain Al (after we paid for the boat ride $5.00per person at one of the park buildings) took us on a trip through the mangroves in a boat which could hold about 20 passengers.  There 4 of us and Captain Al. We needed to leave right away because the tide was going out. If we waited too long the boat would be stuck on the ground beneath the boat,  We saw the mangroves saved for South Florida by Anne Kolb.  If the developers had had their way and destroyed the mangroves, Florida's fish and bird population would be decreased tremendously.  We say an Osprey, Ibis, a tiny crab and later a Raccoon.From the observation deck (5 stories high) we could see Port Everglades, the Atlantic Ocean, and the entire park.There was a wedding being held in the park as well.Wonderful afternoon!

data.title: Inexpensive eco-activity for the land-lovers
data.content: Some in our family went on an early morning fishing trip.  The rest of us found this hidden gem.  This park is run by the local government and costs $2.12 per person.  For this fee, visit the Visitor's Center to see several animals from the mangrove and watch the movie to learn more. There were 3 easy to traverse boardwalks (stroller and wheelchair friendly!) We were there at low tide, so we saw many of the crabs from this habitat.  There were small lizards and a large 2 foot iguana also.  There are several beautiful overlooks.  The lookout tower has an elevator if you need it.  It looks out over the mangrove, the intercostal way and out the ocean.  There were boat tours available on other days that might be interesting.  Also, there would likely be more fish and birds during high tide according the the ranger.  Definitely a place to enjoy with animal and nature lovers.

data.title: Peaceful Escape, Well Maintained Trails
data.content: We went as a group of friends to practice our photography and even though it was Saturday, it was not crowded at all. The trails close to the visitor center are all on raised wooden boardwalks to keep you above the mangroves. We saw lots of tree crabs and I never knew crabs could climb trees before this. The tree crabs are tiny and are also in the mud among the mangroves. Didn't see any birds though so that was disappointing. Winter would probably be better for birds. We didn't try any of the longer trails away from the visitor center because it's way too hot for that in the summer, even in the morning. Would definitely go back in the winter and spend more time. This attraction was very clean, including the restrooms inside the exhibit center. I only gave 4 stars because the woman working the visitor center knew nothing about the trails and couldn't really answer any questions -- or she didn't want to help. Another reviewer mentioned this too. There also weren't any decent maps of the trails at the visitor center. There is a small fee for the exhibit hall and it's worth it to help this very worthwhile nature center.

data.title: Peaceful stroll through nature, but mind the weather
data.content: The center offers several hiking trails of varying length and themes/panoramas, plus an observation tower accessible by elevator or stairs. It also has a somewhat small, indoor "museum" and video theater, plus a gift shop. Do take the weather, especially the temperature into account. We were there in early June and it was already rather hot and muggy. Winter and Spring in SoFlo would be ideal times to visit. I suspect that even the critters were hiding under water or deep in the shade, and would be more visible in cooler weather. We visited with two of the grandchildren and they liked the off-the-path experience.

data.title: Great Campground
data.content: Having lived in the area before I knew CB Smith Park campground was here, but never knew how good it was. The park is very active, especially on weekends with activities like a water park, golf driving range, water skiing and numerous pavilions for cookouts.  The park even has a concert area with shows during the year. The campground is an oasis in the park, set aside and surrounded by lakes.  Sites are large, not like a commercial,campground. Each site has water, electric & sewer as well as well placed bath houses. Recycling and trash are collected at each bath house.  Important to us is that it is dog friendly as long as you follow the normal common sense rules.  The campground is kid friendly with bike paths, a fishing pier and plenty of room to just be kids.  Being surrounded by water, most sites have a water view and a very relaxing feel. Being surrounded by the city, you can hear traffic at times, but nothing you wouldn't expect being this close in. Book early, but remember to check for ongoing activities as some park events can overwhelm the place and intrude on your vacation (like the annual Chili cook off).

data.content: CB Smith is a great park to visit for everything from hosting a birthday party at one of the pavilions to taking golfing lessons to having some fun at their water park. Entrance is only $1.50 per person on the weekends. The water park is about $10 per person unless you go after 3pm and it goes down to about $6.25. data.title: Enjoyable Local Park
data.content: Park is large and has a number of things to do. I enjoy running in the morning through the park, we go and hit golf ball at the range, play at the children's playground, attend company picnics and have gone to the waterpark.  Entrance to the park is free during the week and $1.50 on weekends.  The park can sometimes be a little dirty, but the restrooms are always clean (well as clean as they can be).  We recently went to the water park, first visit since the renovation.  We went during the week and knew that local day camps would be enjoying a day there as well.  While the parking lot was packed, we were able to find plenty of seats and lounges.  The new slides were awesome - lines get a little long at times, but it was never terribly long.  The lazy river would get so packed, that it was almost comical to see the floats all bunched together.  We ended up spending almost all day there.  We had food from the snack bar (slow, but polite service), even though they allow coolers in the park.  Food was reasonably priced and not bad at all.  They had plenty of tables with umbrellas available for rent all day long.  We saw plenty of sheriffs in the park as well as there has been a really bad problem of cars getting broken into while you are off doing something (this is county-wide at all parks).  Admission is a few dollars lower after 3 and plenty of people come in after the day camps leave.  I saw that they don't offer refunds, but give you rain checks based on how long you have been at the water park.  The park itself could definitely use a little TLC - but I enjoy my visits there.

data.title: Waterpark was a bargain
data.content: This review is about the waterpark within CB Smith park (called Paradise Cove). The park is open every day in the summer, and only costs just under $10 a person (adults and children alike). There are two kiddie areas with spray guns, mini-slides, and dump buckets. Both areas have very shallow water (which varies from ankle-depth to mid-calf-depth). One area is themed around fruit and the other has an ocean theme. Very cute, but the buckets beep very loudly right before they dump to encourage the kids to come running, and the constant beeping is a little obnoxious. The kids, though, were super excited by the alert. You can ride double on some of the kiddie slides, which is great if you have very little ones with you. (We had three kids: 11, 10, and 2). The lifeguards let the 11 and 10 year old kids ride with the two year old AT FIRST, then we were told by their relief lifeguards that the toddler had to go with a grownup only. All five of the kiddie slides are nearly identical to one another; too big for little ones to go by themselves, but too small to be of much interest for the bigger kids for long.There is also a lovely lazy river with a lot of interactable objects around it. There are some bombs that kids will operate that force airbubbles up from the ground, squirters and sprayers in another section, and a bridge that may or may not suddenly begin pouring water onto unsuspecting floaters. You have to be in a tube (no free-floating). You can ride double in a tube with your little one.Finally, there are two large slides that entertained my older kids all day long. They are really great, smooth slides, and both are very different from one another. One is fast and rocks you around a lot. The other is slower but has a bigger drop. The wait for these was reasonable even at the busiest part of the day.There are tons of benches, chairs, and loungers scattered around the park. Some shaded, some in the sun, but plenty of room for everyone who was there with us. There are even some grassy areas if you prefer to set up your towel like you're at the beach. They even have covered picnic areas available for rent; these areas aren't very private, but instead are centrally located to all the attractions. There is a grill and some satellite food stations around. We chose not to eat at the park when we saw a big, homemade sign that read "NO REFUNDS" on one of the satellite stations. That scared us away. How many people are getting their food then wanting their money back to justify making a sign?! There are also lockers available for rent and huge restrooms with showers. The restrooms and grounds in general weren't the cleanest, but they certainly weren't gross. The water and wet areas were clean. We found the park to be a lot of fun, especially considering how inexpensive it was. Great way to spend a hot summer day in Florida. And they even have a refund policy in case it rains as is so common here in the summer. Bottom line? If you are in the area, it's a cheap and easy day, but I wouldn't go out of my way to come here unless I was inland visiting family or if I lived in the area. Since we do live in the area, though, we'll definitely be back.

data.title: CB Smith Campground
data.content: Stayed at the CB Smith Park Campground. Beautiful lake views if you can get a site on the lake. Lots of trees and lots of birds to listen to in the morning. No fire pits in rv sites, only in separate tent area. Bbq grill and picnic table at each rv site. Lots of pull-through paved sites for rvs. Electric, sewer and water hook up at each rv site. Laundry facilities. Great huge park for bike riding. Rentals across the lake for sking. There is concerts sometimes across the lake on the lawn. You can hear music at campground. CB Smith is easy access to I75 and convenient to lots of shopping and restaurants. Seems like a safe area although I didn't like that anyone can come into the park at anytime of the night as nobody at the gate at night. There is rangers that patrol a lot though at night. I really liked the park and campground except for no security gate at night and often hearing ambulance sirens from campground due to hospital across the street from the park.

data.title: A very quiet hidden garden of nature.
data.content: First this is a park that is run by Broward county and access is only by boat and the shuttle they have is free (give a couple of bucks in a tip if you can)and runs on the weekend only. I was pleasantly surprised to see what it had to offer . You can spend as little as 45 minutes to 3-4 hours on the island. You can even have a BBQ however everything is bring it yourself as nothing is available on the island.There are very clean bathroom facilities so need to worry about that.The one negative I had is that there were a number of signs obviously giving some info about the wildlife or plant life that were so old they were faded out and as such you missed out on this info. This needs to be revived.Hints:- go in the morning when there is a little more action and the heat is so tough. - Be ready to deal see spiders. They are not dangerous but they are big. The  operators clear the paths in the morning but you need to be on the lookout if you decide to venture off the trails. I suggest picking up a dead palm branch to use in clearing any areas you want to go that have some webs in the way.- Don't make a lot of noise when walking the paths, and look far ahead before looking from side to side as you can see the wildlife. We saw a raccoon walking the path up ahead of us and a 3-4 ft iguana crossed our path. We also were able to catch up with 3 turtles.- Don't be shy to ask the operators working if they had seen any turtles. They often know where the nests are and might be able to help you catch a glimpse of them. -Typically the boat going to the island leaves on the hour, and it comes back at 10 minutes to the hour.-Take your time and enjoy the jungle of an island you are on in the middle of one of the more expensive areas in the US. It is nice to be able to jump on a 3 minute boat ride and sort of go back in time.

data.title: Vacation 2016
data.content: The whole experience was very enjoyable. Our guide Tom picked us up at our Hotel. The ride to the park was very smooth and informative. Tom was very knowledgeable about the area where we were staying and about the Everglades. Gave us some helpful information about places to eat. Escorted us around the park, over to the airboat and was waiting for us when we got back to the park. On the trip back I thought I had left my phone back at the park so he called back to see if it had been found. Thankfully I found it on the floor of the van we were in but he jumped to help me when I thought I had lost it. Delivered us back to our Hotel and helped us out of the van. We really enjoyed the air boat ride, was amazed at all the alligators we saw in the water and how close they came to the boat. I was very glad that we didn't see any snakes in the water or at the park. Terrified of them!!! Alligator show back at the park was the biggest let down if there had to be one but I can't say that I would do it myself. The baby alligator was cute but I think $10 was a bit much for a picture with it?? Overall we were very glad that we included the Park as part of our vacation to Ft. Lauderdale.

data.title: Overall good, here's what to expect
data.content: ProsIt's cool to ride in an airboat in the Florida Everglades. You get to see wild alligators in their natural habitat.The airboat is covered.  Left side, front is the best seat although all seats are good.Noisy, but not that bad.They took a photo of us and we got a free 5x7 print.ConsIt's nearly an hour from Ft Lauderdale.  Best bet is to get the $59 package that includes transportation.They have no rest rooms.  Must use gross port-o-potties.The airboats don't go that fast.  The photo in the ad with the airboat lifting is not what happens.  Also the airboat does not go over grass.  The entire ride was about a mile and the boat stayed in open water.We saw 2 alligators.  They stuck their heads out of the water and the boat got within 10 feet for photos. The boat turned around so both sides could get photos. The excessive begging for tips by the captain made us uncomfortable.The show after the ride was pretty lame.  The highlight was a Gator Boy putting a sluggish alligator's jaw under his chin.  He criticized the crowd for not applauding.  After the show, the animal encounter 'zoo' is only three tiny cages with a pig, raccoons and a turtle. IFor $10 more they'll let you hold a baby alligator and will take your pic.Despite this list of cons, we felt it was worth going

data.title: a good (value for money) experience!
data.content: Was so looking forward to this experience and it didn't disappoint. The airboat ride was fun and exhilarating while still being informative. I know its good to be safe and not sun burnt, but i think the covered boats took away from the raw, local, everglades experience a bit. Hard to decide whether i liked the cover or not, but it would have been good to be able to see out the front of the boat as well as the sides. We sat on the edge of the boat but i dont think it would have been as good an eperience for those in the center seats! TIP: get a seat on the side! They are very organized and when you purchase your ticket you are given a number which they call out on a loud speaker when your boat is ready - bet to the line up when you hear the number before yours so that you are first in line for your boat and can get a side seat! the Aligator show afterwards was good.... we only caught the end of the show because of the ting when our boat arrived back and we couldnt wait for the next one to start because of another engagement... but  i thoroughly enjoyed the part i did see and took about 50 photos. Tip again would be to make sure you are one of the first in to the show (even wait for the next show if you can) because visibility is not easy if you are behind others and if you have little ones you will need to lift them up! All in all - i would recommend this tour and facility to others no problem!!

data.title: OK
data.content: Booked an excursion through Royal Caribbean for time at the Everglades Holiday Park on the final day of our cruise and then to be dropped off at Miami airport.  We were picked up and taken to the holiday park.  There was lots of waiting around as our tour guide was waiting for guidance about our itinerary.  We finally got told to go and join the queue for the alligator show.  This was good and quite entertaining, however there were numerous references made about having to leave a tip as it was an unpaid job??  We then left this and had our photo taken with a baby Alligator.  Following this we left for the airboat ride.  This was good fun and we got to take a few photos despite not seeing much wildlife (to be expected).  The guide again went on a few times about leaving a tip and stating how much he wanted.  We left the boat unable to leave a tip to then be publicly humiliated.  Now let me be clear.  This excursion was NOT free.  We paid good money for this.  We were due to fly home that evening and had run out of cash.  We always tip when we have a good service as we know this is expected in the states but this place just expects it and will humiliate you if you don’t tip.  Unprofessional and I would not return or recommend to anyone.

data.title: Something to do while waiting to head to a late afternoon flight
data.content: While the airboat ride itself was a fun experience, I did have a bit of an off experience being that a very large spider was walking back and forth on the front dash of the boat casually trying to figure out where to go. It was a bit disconcerting.  The alligators were a bit peeved that we got too close and one just swam away to avoid us, and seeing that an airboat was coming up to them ever 15 min, I could see why. I felt bad for them and the fact they were basically being harassed in their home. The alligator show was, well, strange. A guy who called himself an alligator wrestler made some really silly and sometimes off colour jokes while he waited for the bleachers to fill up for the show. Some of the comments I didn't think were too appropriate but he continued. He pulled one reluctant alligator over to the sand pit and opened the alligator's mouth, put his face in it and that was about it for the event of his acrobatics. He didn't really talk much about the conservation or protection of the animals so I felt like it was a not well thought out show. We did get to see and pet a baby alligator named Loki and have our picture taken with her for about 10 sec before having to duck away back to the buses. The one thing that was a bit of a downer, was that it seemed everyone was asking, repeatedly, for tips. I know many folks in these types of jobs work with lower pay and rely on tips, but when we're reminded multiple times and there are signs everywhere telling us, it becomes a bit frustrating. And not all of us carry cash anymore, so being made to feel like idiots because we didn't tip the person wasn't a pleasant experience. Considering how expensive the shop items were, $4.00 for a small bottle of water, I'd assume they paid the employees better by this point. Guess not. It wasn't a bad way to spend an afternoon, just wasn't fabulous.

data.content: We paid $150 for 4 people to do the animal encounter which totally sucked in everyway imaginable. The brochure that lured us to come showed actual encounters with animals which were locked away in cages asleep. The presentation seemed rushed. Held baby alligator and reptiles for a quick picture before being taken away. These turned out to be some very expensive pictures. We can go to our local pet store in Indiana and hold the reptiles we held today. We saw someone holding a baby gator with some employees and when we asked to hold it, we were denied. data.title: NEVER GO HERE
data.content: The lady working the counter was the rudest person I ever met.  She hated her job and let everyone know about it.  She reminded me of the lady form the movie Goonies.  The person driving the air boat complained how he is under paid and he works off tips and how he is struggling to feed his family (no joke).   The guy that did the alligator show only had 3 fingers which was entertaining, he was really trashy, it was great and amusing and interesting.  Other than that show everything else was horrible.  Two tips, if you are going on an air boat ride go during the winter months; the alligators rarely come out during the summer months.  We went in Aug and didn't see an alligator. Tip number 2; NEVER go to Everglades Holiday Park!

data.title: Tourist Trap
data.content: If you're looking for a place in which you will be reminded when you board the Axel Tour van for your trip over that gratuities are not included in the admission, want to be charged $10 to buy a picture of yourself in front of an alligator sign, or if you want to pay $5 to use your camera to take a picture with an alligator than this place is for you. I found the guide to be rather annoying and was confused by his convoluted stories. I wish I had learned more about the Everglades and wish I had seen more alligators too!  Perhaps for a family with young children this might be fun, but for my wife and myself this was probably one of our only disappointments on our vacation. I may have been more inclined to tip, if they weren't constantly asking.

data.title: Everglades
data.content: If you've never been to the Everglades this is a great introduction.  You get the airboat ride, the stunning scenery, alligators (wild) and a show.  The boat is enclosed so you aren't baking, and it's about an hour ride.  All of the staff are volunteers who are animal tamers, naturalists, conservationists and work in the area.   I was amazed at how glassy the water could be when the wind was blowing.  The birds are amazing.  John, our boat captain was great.  Crazy lady who was wresting the alligator.  Give her some kudos!  All in all, an enjoyable time and learned a ton about what's real and not real on tv about alligators.

data.title: In Search of Bubba!
data.content: Upon arrival, you feel you have come to the end are of civilization. You are getting an up close look at the Everglades, a wildlife preserve about 20 minutes outside the center of Ft. Lauderdale.  Airboat tours and rides are offered daily from 9 a.m. until dark. Your trip starts with a airboat ride through the surrounding wetlands and it is a thrill when the captain opens up the throttle and the boat is skimming over the water at 55 MPH. During the hour long ride you are introduced to the various forms of wildlife and are constantly looking for alligators. We spotted three on our ride but the big one, Bubba, was no where to be found. After our airboat ride we were entertained at the gator show in the "gator pit" and got to hold a baby alligator at the end. You not only view alligators in their own natural habitat but are taught about their health and wellbeing. Included in general admission is a free picture taken before you board the airboat which is a nice token to bring home. A gift shop is on the premises as well as a small cafe for beverages and light snacks. For an additional fee, bus pick ups can be arranged at the various hotels in Ft. Lauderdale. It is best to arrive early and avoid the crowds and heat.Check out the web site for Everglades Holiday Park for money saving coupons.

data.title: Go In the Morning!
data.content: We arrived around 9:30 and so did not have to wait for an airboat.  The down side is that we had the second boat out and the guides didn't know where the gators were snoozing yet.  But it seems they are familiar with several usual spots.  We only saw 2 gators but we saw some iguanas and a lot of interesting birds.  Children on board were given bread to feed the birds who came right to the side of the boat.  Tickets are $23 for adults and I think $15 for children.  The gator show followed right after the nearly 1-hr ride.  Tip:  go all the way down for the show.  We watched from the ramp through the fence, but I wish we had gone all the way down in front because those fences were dropped down at the tops just before the show started and those people had a better view.  There were 12 gators in the enclosure and "gator girl" pulled a 200-pounder out of the water by his tail to do the show.  It was not a long show, but was very good, although it's rather stinky there!  Restrooms are available, and were clean.  Parking is free.

data.title: Beautiful scenery & family fun!
data.content: We decided to make a quick stop on our way home to Tampa after a cruise in Miami. We drove from the port after debarkation and it was about a 45 minute drive. We arrived around 11-11:30 and it was fairly busy, but not crowded. We purchased our tickets and then waited for our group to be called. There is plenty to look at and plenty of seats while you wait. There is a small gift shop, convenience type store and a little food window. Our group was called about 15 mins later, we lined up and each family had their photo taken in front of a boat before entering. At the end of the tour we were able to buy that along with a key chain for $10. Our boat driver was very knowledgeable & funny and made the trip fun. The scenery is beautiful and we saw plenty of gators. After the air boat tour we followed the crowd to the gator wrestling show, it gets very packed in that small area so try to find a good spot quickly. Since my son & his dad are huge fans of the show Gator Boys, they were hoping to see one of the guys featured on the show. But instead Ashley Lawrence from the show was working with the gators that day and they were just as pleased seeing her ;). The show lasted about 15 mins and then you can have pics taken with a small gator if you'd like. Glad we stopped here, it was a nice and we all enjoyed it.

data.title: Disappointing
data.content: Having never ridden in an airboat I was expecting more. The fact they are covered made sitting on the front row extremely hot and difficult to see as the sun was beating down through an incredibly dirty piece of plexiglass windshield. We saw a few aquatic plants, buzzards sitting in a tree, tiny birds skipping across the water plants and spent most our time looking for a gator. Finally located a 4 foot gator swimming away from us toward vegetation cover.After the boat ride I was hopeful the Gator Boys show and the gift shop would rescue this trip. Neither did. The gator show was made up of dragging a lethargic gator away from the fence and jumping on its' back. The "gator 'rassler" pulled the gator's snout up and placed it under his chin, then he did the "face off" move and that was it. In all, the gator show lasted maybe 10 minutes.If you're going here expecting to see one of the TV stars don't gamble your whole trip on that or you will probably be disappointed.In hindsight I wish I had considered one of the other Everglades adventures.

data.title: Not What It Used To Be - Better Options Out There
data.content: Was there before it became "Home of the Gator Boys" and it was nice. No more - just about ANYWHERE is nicer. If you think you're going to come here and "see some alligators" they're not going to let that happen without you forking over some dough for the air boat ride. ALL the gators are kept behind screening and you only get to see the gators and wrestling show if you buy an air boat ticket. What if you can't take the air boat? Too bad. My son is in a wheelchair and the vibration of the boat would threaten his medical condition. When I told them we couldn't do the air boat the response was that was the only way they do it. Thankfully, as we were walking away a kind employee who overheard me slipped us a piece of paper allowing us to get into the "show" which is the only place you can see the gators. The "show" is a 10 minute "wrestling" match where someone talks about the gators and does a couple tricks with them. It's okay but nothing incredible. Seeing how we got into the show for free we made sure to give the presenter (his name was Chris - a tall blond guy) a $10 tip and then paid the $5 to take a picture with the baby alligator. I asked Chris if he minded if we took his picture as well and he gave the most sarcastic and condescending, "wow, I can't think of anything more fun". He said he has been on the Animal Planet show a few times (he's not one of the main guys and I didn't recognize him) so maybe he thinks celebrities are supposed to act arrogant (I felt a little embarrassed for him). Nevertheless, there are MUCH better options out there from Billy Swamp to even just driving through Alligator Alley and looking out the window. I can't really speak regarding the air boat (there are tons of them around anyway) but this place went from something fun and cool to something sad. I wouldn't recommend it to anyone.

data.title: One of a kind experience
data.content: Everglades Holiday Park is South Florida's premier gateway to the state's most exciting natural attraction-the Everglades. The park started nearly three decades ago by George M. Bridges who build the first airboat by hand in his backyard in 1982. The park is a family fun entertainment destinations and offers everything from guided Everglades airboat tours and live alligator presentations to food, souvenirs and fresh water fishing,A moms review:Visiting the Everglades has been on my, "places to visit list" for a very long time. So when we received an opportunity to review Everglades Holiday Park during our visit to Florida I just had to say yes. Everglades Holiday Park is located in Fort Lauderdale, Florida so it took us about 3 1/2 hours to get there from the Orlando area but the drive was well worth it.We arrived at the park around 11 am. Parking was plentiful and it was very easy to locate the gift shop where we received our airboat tour ticket. The gift shop was quite large and offered snacks, souvenirs and fishing gear. There were well maintained restrooms located just outside of the gift shop. There was also a deli located next to the gift shop in case you need to grab a bite to eat. After receiving our airboat tour tickets we went outside to sit on the covered porch in front of the gift shop to wait for our tour number to be called. In about 10 minutes they announced our tour number over the PA system and we proceeded down to the boat dock.Once at the boat dock a staff member gathered our family and took a souvenir photo. And guess what the photo is included in the cost of your tickets! How cool is that? No need to pay another $20+ for a photo to remember your experience.At this point the kids were getting really excited.....okay so was I. Our Captain walked us up the dock to the boat and we piled in. The boats seat 20+ people and are covered so you don't have to worry about melting in the Florida sun! After our Captain Mike went over some rules we were off on our 60 minute thrilling airboat tour of the Everglades.WOW! We learned so much in 60 minutes. Mike told us the history of the area, how the Native Americans lived off the land, and how to survive if you ever get lost in the Everglades (which I hope never happens...eek). He also showed us the numerous flora and fauna of the area and yes we did get to see a couple alligators...one of them was only a few feet away from the boat! Our Captain really made our experience a fun and remarkable one. It is one that we will never forget. He was funny, informative and you could tell he was very dedicated to his job. **Important note: bring cash to tip your airboat Captain and the Gator Boys that do the presentation...they deserve it. The Everglades Holiday Park airboat experience is perfect for all ages and a must for nature enthusiasts, thrill seekers and artists!After our airboat tour we picked up our souvenir photo and headed up to the waiting area for our gator show with the famous "Gator Boys"! If you don't know who the Gator Boys are let me tell you a little bit about them. The Gator Boys are a group of people (and not just boys there is a woman too) dedicated to rescuing nuisance alligators around Florida. Their reality show airs on Animal Planet, in fact many of their episodes were filmed at Everglades Holiday Park. When it was time for our show they walked us down to a covered walkway located in front of the "gator pit." **Important note: Everglades Holiday Park is in the process of building an arena area for future shows! The 20 minute show is an adrenalin-charged good time filled with exciting stunts, tricks and some of the best entertainment around. It is also very educational which is a plus for our homeschooling family! The show is very animal friendly and in fact the Gator Boys Alligator Rescue actually helps nuisance alligators by giving them a place to live and eat in a natural setting. These gators, if not rescued would have been euthanized...instead they are now animal ambassadors helping to break down alligator stereotypes!After the show is over you can head over to the photo area to capture some more special memories. For a small fee you can get a memorable experience and photo holding a baby alligator, snake or other critter (animals do vary but they generally always have a baby alligator available for a photo shoot). Look at their grins. They were in absolute heaven.We give Everglades Holiday Park 5 stars. The cost, experiences and staff were all stellar. We highly recommend this experience to any family looking for a one of a kind way to spend their time in Florida! I promise you will not be disappointed. When I posted our photos to social media several followers told me they had similar experiences with Everglades Holiday Park and visit every year when they vacation in Florida!

data.title: Gator Boys Comes To Into Perspective
data.content: Paul and Jimmy are rarely there. I just wanted to let you know that up front. This outing at the everglades was a first, but not the last. When you get there you must buy a ticket for the air boat ride and to get in the show ( about 30 dollars for adult). we waited for about 30 minutes. they take your picture before you get on the boat. Can be purchased after the boat ride. we did came out great (10 dollars). The air boat ride for us lasted about 1 hour. We saw alligators in a few different spots. Each boat driver seems to have its own bet bird out in the everglades. When you stop it hopped right on his arm when he came and sat in the seating area on the boat. we were within 3 feet of two alligators (cool). The show was with one of the gator boys on the show he did a very nice job. It lasts about 20 minutes. You can even hold a baby alligator if you want for a $5 dollar donation to the alligator rescue part of the park. It as cool cant wait to go back.

data.title: Good Way to take a Peak at the Glades
data.content: Holiday Park is just a few miles from the house and is a regular stop when we have guests that want to see the a small part of the Everglades Conservation Area. This not part of the Everglades National Park, but it is still very cool to see. Visits here are safe and clean and perfect for the casual visit with or without an airboat ride. This is much better choice for a quick visit than any other point farther north. Just like everything else around here, the place has changed a lot over the past ten years. Today, the "bait and beer" shop is gone, and the air boat fleet is huge. Most of the fishing trips have moved to other ramps and docks because the place is really busy now. The tourists arrive by the busload when cruise ships are in port so the parking lot is actually paved now. The County has taken over the operation so it is a lot cleaner than it probably ever has been. Parents don't need to worry any more about having their small children grabbed by one of the toothless gator poachers that used to hang around the main building while living in one of the of the derelict trailers on the property. All of that junk has been removed from behind the main building, and the entire area is being converted into a County campground.  Now that reality TV shows use the area, it is really tame and family oriented. For tourists, this is a fast and easy way to see the northern views of the Glades. The short drive in is along one of the main flood control canals and a major pumping station sits at the end of the canal next to the parking lot. The dike along the Eastern edge of the swamp has a road on top and from there you can look out over this part of the conservation area. Most of the airboat drivers do a good job of informing and entertaining guests. The trip includes a stop at an "Indian Village" which is cheesy, but kids love it. The local alligators hang around in the canals to make sure everybody gets to see one of them unless it gets cold. Most trips get to see local birds and turtles, sometimes snakes and fish. This is one of the best "gator and swamp" experiences in the State. It is very accessible with good facilities and can usually handle the crowds. If you want to feel as if you went out to convene with nature, but still wanted to be within 10 miles of the nearest Starbucks, this is the place.

data.title: Cruel to their animals
data.content: We did the four hour  tour. Our van driver Tommy P gets five stars. He was fun, very socially adept and informative. The part of Everglades Holiday Park that has animals should be shut down. We could smell the poop permeating the air upon arrival. No animal should live in that. The baby alligator photo op was cruel. The little guy had his mouth taped shut and some days , from the number of tours  they must have over a hundred people handling him.The airboat pilots were unorganized and mine was rude. Tom told our group to make sure to stay together. The pilots did not check. When I told our pilot we were supposed to stay together, he told me to get on or leave when I was simply trying to tell him what I was told. Sure enough one couple were put on a different boat and wound up half an hour late arriving back with our group.

data.title: First Tour for Captain but Very Enjoyable
data.content: Part of our family was visiting and I decided to show them the wilder side of Southeast Florida. You can take I95 to Griffin Rd. and take it  far west into the Glades where the road ends and the airboats await. We arrived in the early morning before any tours started. We paid for the tour and the "Gator Boys" presentation.It turned out that our airboat captain was conducting her first tour. She was nervous but kept us informed and entertained. We spotted a fair amount of birds which she identified for us and stopped and provided us with a 360 degree view of new hatchlings. We saw several gators in their native habitat and had one swim under our boat since he/she didn't want tourists staring .She was able to show us how fast these boats can go when we got to open water. We were met bak at the dock by all the captains who weren't giving tours at that time. This was not a welcome back for us but it was for our guide. She received her Captain's hat and rather than being covered with champagne, they soaked her with bottled water.The " Gator Boys" are from an "Animal Planet" show. This was not traditional alligator wrestling but was concerned with the preservation of the American alligator. The lead "Gator" gave an interesting show and kept our attention. We all had a good time.

data.title: Simply just amazing!
data.content: We had the best time at this place! First, we had the greatest animal encounter session with Jessica! We were only 3 couples, so we felt really good taken care of! She taught us a lot about the animals she showed us- the raccoon, the tortoise, the BROWN AND WHITE SCUNK! (I thought they only came in black/white), a tiny alligator and last but not least the snake, which I was afraid of at first, but it was so calm and well behaving that all my fears (almost) vanished! Jessica was a lot of fun too, she had many both good and bad jokes, but mainly many interesting facts - she knew her stuff! We got to hold all animals except the raccoon, as they are picky lovers and we didn't hold the tortoise either, but she walked around, so we had out chance to touch her.Next off, we har a boat ride with Captain Robert, who did a very lively telling as we went about the rivers. He told us about the seagrass, the peppercorns, the yellow lilly, the vultures and generally all the edibles in the area. At first we didn't see any alligators, as it had been raining that morning, and gators go under water in rainy weather. We were in luck, though! Captain Rob went out of his was, going off route to show us just one gator he had seen earlier- and we were in luck! There was a female alligator! She wasn't very big, but we got some nice shots and Captain Rob made sure to turn the boat around a few times to make sure everyone had a good chance to see her!As we went further, we saw another gator and a bit after that, Captain Rob sounded like he was going crazy! Shouting about a HUGE gator and none of us saw anything! Then he turned the boat around, and surely, there it was! It was massive! So impressive! And it sorta chased the boat around, so that was both exciting and worrying! It came really close! Amazing experience! Last but not least, we saw the gator show! We were very impressed with how the Gator Boy (we're sorry, we don't remember your name!) He just walked into the gator pit like he owned the place and talked about the different alligators in there, lifted the tail of the biggest one in there, which was just as big as him - the tail, that is!! Very impressive! He also had some both good and bad jokes, but most importantly, he put on a good show, showed us the mouth of the gator and pulled off some daring tricks! Thank you all for some great experiences! We hope the best for you all and for the Everglades preservation!

data.title: Airboat Tour, Alligator Rescue Show AND Animal Encounter
data.content: I encourage everyone to also do the animal encounter.  Our guide, Emilio is a soft spoken young man with a gentle approach to the animals.  This is a very close-up, hands on, informative encounter with animals such as a pig, a skunk, an albino boa, and a small alligator. They take a lot of pictures as a part of the encounter.  (at no charge) The airboat tour is great and fun for the entire family.  We were an arms length from the gators. data.title: A very pleasant activity for the family
data.content: This is a very family friendly activity. Little o new enjoyed it but adults equally enjoy the activity. The airboat ride is very good and you get to learn a lot about the Everglades which it is a river and not a swamp as many think. Also you see quite a bit of bird life and alligators in the wild which was pretty fun. A bit of disappointment that not many fishes were seen. The Alligator show was very nice and professional and it is good to see that they take care of them pretty well. The two free photos is an added bonus. If you are in the military ask for discount I got 50% off of my ticket.  The only reason I did not give five stars is because they say ear protection is included but none was given. Suggest you bring your own as boat ride is very loud.

Small cafe which sadly was not very good so I wouldn't recommend eating there.

data.title: Excellent airboat tour of Everglades to see alligators
data.content: We really enjoyed our airboat tour to see the Everglades and alligators. We arrived early and it was not crowded so the captain was able to let us sit at the ends of 2 rows to best view the sights. We got up close views of 5 alligators. The captain patiently maneuvered the boat for everyone to see the gators, taking a lot of time with each gator. The captain explained the plant and animal life surrounding us. It was a little difficult at times hearing him via the speaker system. Overall, this was a fantastic tour. Everyone knows teenagers can be miserable, it was awesome seeing the giant smiles on our teenagers during the tour. The captain requests and accepts tips at the conclusion of the ride. The alligator show afterward was good also. It's sad that the presenter is a volunteer and has to request tips, as Everglades Holiday Park does not employee them for insurance purposes. Seems a bit rediculous and stingy toward those who make the show!The price we paid was very affordable. Our resort provided coupons for 50% off. Just ask!

data.title: Passionate people making a difference
data.content: As we live in Florida and have been fans of the Gator Boys tv show, we have wanted to visit the Everglades Holiday Park for some time.  The kids loved being there in person after seeing so many episodes of the show.  The air boat ride was excellent and our Captian, Bucky was knowledgeable and amusing.  The alligator show was equally informative as it was entertaining,  We were able to meet Ashley, from the show, who was very friendly.  The most impressive aspect of the park is the fact that the employees (with the exception of the store front/retail aspect) work for free.  They are all volunteers and you can tell how passionate they are about conservation of the alligators and the everglades.  It was a valuable lesson to my kids who couldn't believe people will work for free when they find something that they love.  A great outing and life lesson all in one summer afternoon, what more could a parent ask for...

data.title: Nice budget, quick, excursion close to Miami
data.content: We took a bus through Xcursions USA to the Everglades Holiday Alligator Park. We chose this one since it was a shorter time (about 45 min bus ride) to the Everglades and  lower priced than some others. I felt like we got our money's worth on it and enjoyed the afternoon. The everglades boat tour was interesting, our guide did a nice job explaining the ecology of the region and pointing out alligators and other wildlife. The only downside was there was one staff person who was quite abrupt and rude telling people to get in line. She acted like we were an inconvenience to her. We had to wait in the sun instead of the shade just a few feet away. We were the first ones in line from our group and still there was no smiling or conversation, just bossing and directing us around. Then other groups were taken ahead of us. The store with souvenirs was good - i found a cute t-shirt for my son. Staff there was pleasant and helpful. There was also a cafe on the grounds and it smelled good although we didn't order any food.. The alligator show was fine. The 'gator boy' guy who led it talked a fair amount about how the alligators arrive there and how much they care for them but there wasn't a whole lot of interaction with them. He did get ahold of one and do a few tricks holding its mouth, etc. which was impressive. I wouldn't want to be in that tank! Then it was mostly a plea for more money to support their organization. There was then a small series of pens with other animals - a pig, raccoons, and a baby alligator (which we got to see and touch but not hold since we weren't buying the additional $10 photo).

data.title: Short but exciting airboat ride through the Everglades
data.content: We disembarked at Fort Lauderdale and wanted to see the Everglades in a short amount of time before we boarded our plane back to California. Princess offers a disembarkation tour to the Everglades Holiday Park with drop off at the Fort Lauderdale airport by noon. Getting off the ship was quick and efficient. After picking up our luggage, we were shown to a bus and our luggage was loaded. Very interesting guide told us all about Ft. Lauderdale and the Everglades as we drove. Clean bus, comfortable seats, huge windows. Arriving at the Everglades Holiday Park, we went first to see the Gator Boys Alligator show, a close up view behind a chain link fence where the Gator guy talked as he demonstrated some "tricks" with a feisty alligator, very entertaining, my 8 yr. old grandson loved it. Great photo ops or they would take your photo holding a small alligator. Well stocked gift shop and food was sold next door. We were then led down to the dock where airboats were taking off on 30 minute tours. We were aboard the Looney, with Captain Mike as the operator. Mike was very knowledgable about the gators and the Everglades in general. We cruised fast to show what the airboat could do and then very slowly into reedy areas where Mike knew the gators to hang out. Sure enough, we sighted 4 and Mike described their habits and even told us names he had given them and some alligator cultural and folk tales. At one place, Mike called out for Grumpy and out he came, swam right out alongside our boat and seemed to recognize Mike's voice. Really interesting and fun but too short. If you go, try to allow enough time for the one hour airboat ride and be sure to see the free one man gator show. Observed small bus in the parking lot with a sign that you could arrange pickups from your hotel. All in all, highly recommend that if you are in Miami/Ft. Lauderdale vicinity, make time to experience the Everglades. Price is reasonable, park is clean, ship operators do an awesome job in a short time. Be sure to wear sunscreen and a hat since the sun is blazing hot year round.

data.title: Beauty of the Everglades
data.content: On Jan.3rd 2009 I decided to take my friend and my Granddaughter for a little adventure to Everglades Holiday Park.    We got off late in the afternoon.  We seen a alligator show first .  I was so impressed with the trainer who seemed real in touched with the kids.  He feed the gators chicken legs quarters.  He told them of their habitat and put his head in the gators mouth.  After... for just $5.00 you can hold a baby alligator.  Now for a 8 year old this is the greatest wildlife experience.   After that we  visited the gift shop and feed the peacocks which roomed wild in area.   We then went to the dock to take the airboat ride.  First you wait for a photographer to take you picture.  When our turn arrived,  I asked if our boat captain could join us.  We had a great picture taken of our group facing the sun.  As we border our Captain introduced himself as Mike and welcomed us.  We then took off and and it was fun to ride through the marsh like waters and see the sun sparkling off the water. The captain then stopped and told us to look to our left where there was a group of birds perched in some trees Mike was very knowledgeable of the wildlife and the vegetation. I even learned a few things. He also show my granddaughter a tree gator which then the entire boat woooo'd at the site.  When we seen the alligators Mike mad a couple of turnabouts for people to get the best shot with their cameras.  He also sat in the boat with us for a short while and told us some history of the everglades made a few joke and made it a point to remember some of our names.   When retuning to the dock he thanked us for coming and offered his hand to help us onto the dock. If you do not know what a tree gator is and you would like to see one, you have to take this airboat ride.We had a great time. Thank you Everglades Holiday Park and thanks Mike for making it so interesting!

data.title: Alligators, Iguanas, and Birds -- Oh My!
data.content: I had the pleasure of visiting Everglades Holiday Park the afternoon of Dec. 29.  Jessica at Animal Encounters was very informative about the animals in her care, and we were able to hold a young alligator, a boa, and a chubby brown and white skunk.  We were also able to pet an opossum.  The brown and white skunk was new to me, the others I've already encountered in my lifetime, but this time was a pleasure.Our airboat ride was a blast.  Captain Chaos, the Alligator Whisperer, found cute little Bunny.  She came swimming toward the boat and swam around showing the length of her body and smiling.  Someone mentioned, in another review, that the gator was obviously a robotic fake, if he was on our boat, I wish he had tried to pet her.  They're wild animals, not robots.  No one can control where and how many may be seen.  To see one in the wild was fantastic.  The iguanas were amazing, so many large males sunning on rocks or sleeping in the trees.  The birds were beautiful, some that I've only seen in pictures.  Even Vulture Island was fun to see, with those big guys just roosting up in the trees.  Flowering trees and water plants all serving their purpose to keep the everglades and their inhabitants healthy and well-fed.  Loud motors, yes, they're loud, but not ear-splitting.  How loud do you turn up your car radio for "Bohemian Rhapsody" or "We Are The Champions"?  There ya go.  Thank you, Captain Chaos for an enjoyable, interesting, and safe ride.  Your passion and love of the Everglades is so apparent and infectious.On to the Gator Show.  Paul's jokes were good, not corny, the information priceless.  If I ever meet up with a gator, I'll know that he really doesn't want to hurt me and I can turn and run like hell.  On the way out there is a clear box for donations to help with the preservation of these amazingly beautiful animals.  Please help the cause and leave something.  The Captains deserve good tips also, they're doing their best to give you a great adventure.I guess you could say I enjoyed the few hours I spent yesterday.  Thanks to Captain Chaos and also to Captain KC (female Captain) for introducing me to Everglades Holiday Park.  I will forever be their cheerleader.

data.title: Everglades Education
data.content: When is a swamp not a swamp?  When it's a wildlife preserve with guided tours. We visited during Spring Break, but the wait for an airboat ride wasn't too bad. Search online in advance for coupons/discounts. I used my smartphone while standing in line and got $3 off for four people just by showing a QR code to the cashier. Airboat tour lasted about 40 minutes, and was very educational about the formation of the Everglades and its inhabitants. We saw a variety of interesting flora and fauna, and our boat driver was knowledgeable. I recommend a camera with a zoom, as it's possible to get only so close to the alligators before they slide away. Still very impressive. The accompanying gator show is brief and designed to support The Gator Boys activities, but it was fine... No false advertising there.

data.title: INTERESTING AND EDIFYING
data.content: The airboat captain was very informative about the Everglades as he piloted a boatload of us passengers through and around the sawgrass and waterways. We saw alligators, of course. Our captain pointed out iguanas resting in trees along a waterway. Iguanas are not native to the Everglades. Caiman have been spotted in the Glades, we were told. Apparently they were pets that grew too big, so the owners dumped them into the Everglades. The Everglades is now rife with pythons, particularly the Burmese variety, our pilot/guide informed us. And they are decimating native mammals, like bobcats, otters, rabbits, and mice. And taking a heavy toll on birds. The giant snakes also take down deer and hogs, but populations of these two mammals so far seem able to sustain this culling. There are non-native fish in the Everglades waters, our pilot said. He mentioned a huge piranha that had been caught by a fisherman. Various birds, on the water, in the air, in trees, were pointed out to us. Even though I hail from south Florida, this airboat ride/tour was most informative.

data.title: Interesting!
data.content: We went as a group of 8 ranging from teens to seniors. We really enjoyed our time in the air boat. Our captain, Tonya, was very energetic and informed. We saw 3 gators (they call them dragons) and many birds. Tonya manged to lure 2 of them into the boat with some bread as a treat. We also got so see Batman from the t.v. show interact with the gators. After the air boat trip, we went to a gator show. We were told that they rescue gators that are in places that they shouldn't be for free and bring them back to the park. The area contained about 25 gators, the water looked dirty and the space was small. A girl went into the area, pulled out a gator and did a couple of daring things with it (i.e. the face off move where she opened the gators mouth and put her chin on top of the gators nose). After this, you can have a picture taken with a snake or a baby gator (that has electrical tape around its mouth :( I didn't like this part. The workers also say that due to the high-risk nature of their jobs that they don't get paid and constantly ask for tips. There is a restaurant on-site as well as a gift shop. You do get one complimentary photo before you enter the air boats. The area where you watch the show as well as the air boats are covered so that you don't bask in the sun. There is also a misting station on the eave of the gift shop. The park is also undergoing some sort of construction when we visited.

data.title: Deaf from airboat motor
data.content: On May 8, My husband and I brought my son to the Everglades Holiday Park for an airboat tour. We do this whenever guests or family come to visit!On this day we were put on an airboat with no top. This is not the norm, but a boat was out of commission and we were told this one was better!  I was concerned because it was a hot day.The problem was that we were seated in the back row. There were only 3 of us so I was seated in the middle. The NOISE from the engine was so loud I could feel it vibrating in my head. I plugged my ears with tissue and held my my hands over them and hoped that was enough!It wasn’t. My ears remain stuffed one week later and the tinnitus I am experiencing makes it difficult for me to hear normal conversation. I will be going to an ENT next week but know that the damage is done. It is beyond me why they don’t offer earplugs and avoid seats like the one I was put in. I am 70 years old. So at least I don’t have to live with this deafness for too many more years. Let’s hope they didn’t seat a child in this seat!

data.title: Lots of fun, good value.
data.content: I did a lot of research before picking which airboat ride to do while in the area and I'm glad we picked Everglades Holiday Park. First off, it was the closest park to our hotel in Weston, only about 20 minutes away. It was also one of the cheapest running about $25 for adults. They have an Internet coupon for $3 off as well as a military discount which was 50% off! They had some others like a senior discount, etc. The airboat ride was pretty interesting. It was in a large 30 person airboat so the tour wasn't very personal but the boat had a roof which was really nice to keep our 2 year old out of the sun. The ride was only an hour so there wasn't time to go very far but we did see 2 alligators, 1 small 2 footer and one mom about 8 feet and also got to see her nest of mud which was pretty cool. We also saw a lot of different birds. They had an alligator show after the tour by the gator boys who you may have seen on animal planet. It was interesting and you got to get up close to a bunch of big alligators and touch a little one if you wanted. They did charge for lots of little stuff like a group picture at the airboat ride and to hold the alligator or to sit on one. They also asked for tips and donations but they pretty much earned it. It wasn't the most incredible tour I've ever been on but I can't think of any reason not to give it a 5 of 5. It was close, inexpensive and met all my expectations.

data.title: Awful Experience - Dishonest Employees
data.content: We went recently and had two younger children with us (10 and 7). After providing a wait time of 20 minutes to get on the boat (#36), they told us to not order lunch as it might not be ready by the time we had to get on the boat. So us and our young kids did not eat as we thought we were going right on the boat. About 25 minutes later they called our number to go watch the show instead because they were short on captains (we were told by Jeff). So we watched the show which consisted of a woman dragging an alligator out and poking and prodding it (and in our opinion was bordering on abuse of animals that had no interest in being treated that way). Afterwards we waited in line for another 30 minutes after they called our number in cue in front of the boats before we gave up. Hearing that they were loading boat #41 at the same time as ours was the final dagger. We had hungry kids, had been there nearly two hours, and were being shuffled around like cattle. A trip to the office for a refund did not help our opinion of them in any way. RJ was unable to grasp the concept, offered a refund finally (but only partially), and then bizarrely took back the offer of the refund based on the premise that I was rude to him. I have the encounter on video and will be disputing the charges. A wooden sign stating “no refunds” does not absolve them from providing the service they advertised and we paid for. Choose another place that cares about the customer, the animals, and their experience.

data.title: Autism Friendly!
data.content: This place is fantastic!  I have a son with moderate nonverbal Autism. The day we arrived,  there was a slight crowd and my son was irritable. I asked at the counter if I bought tickets for us and my son refused to go on the boat,  if they'd issue a refund?  They did something better,  they took my son and I to an empty boat not being used,  and let my son get on and get comfortable.  In addition to that,  Mechanic Bill loaned us his personal pair of noise cancelling headphones since the boats are pretty loud.  Bill spoke to our captain,  Casey and had me sit in a certain spot on our boat.  I was instructed to wave if I needed assistance with my son,  and a rescue boat could come and pick us up and bring us back if necessary.  Luckily,  it wasn't necessary.  Because I was allowed to show my son what we were doing before we did it,  he was comfortable.  He LOVED going fast on the boat! Thank you Bill, Casey,  and everyone else at Holiday Park!

data.title: Well worth it..
data.content: I dont know about anybody else's experience but when we went today.. my family had a blast. ok so we may be "Northerners" .. but we have never been on a Airboat before. Having read other reviews before we went.. we did bring water because it was Hot and brought some mosquito spray.. (which mosquitos werent bad at all). The Airboat ride was awesome. the captain was funny & extremely knowledgable.. ride was about and hour and we saw 3 Gators.. he also showed us some birds which flew over and the kids fed them by hand..  it was worth it. After, we saw the Gator Boys show which was around 10minutes long.. they informed us about the Gators & showed us some tricks. I dont know about anybody else, but I enjoyed the Gator show.. I mean how long should it be??  How many times you want to see somebody attempt to stick their head in the Gator's mouth before he gets caught?? My kids loved it and thats all that matters.. we tipped the Airboat Captain and the Gator Boys.. my thought is.. why not?? They deserved it.. yeah they said Gratuities are Appreciated & we felt they deserved it.. I certainly would prefer tipping them as opposed to a Bum or somebody holding up a fake sign on I-95 begging for money... I think it was 100% worth it and would go back again.. Bathroom was clean and the staff was friendly!!!! Definately bring Water if you go during summer months!!! Only bummer.. sell stuff that says GATOR BOYS on it.. tshirts, hats.. etc.. other than that .. was well worth it..

data.title: Somewhat disappointing trip
data.content: The park itself was very well maintained and in much better shape than what they had at the beginning of their show, "The Gator Boys?" But, therein lies the problem! There was no hint of ANY of the Gator boys any longer except a few photos? I was truly hoping to get to meet or at least see some or even one of them, however I was truly disappointed by the answers I received except from one young lady who I assume told me the sad truth? She said the Gator Boys including Paul Bedard are Never there any more but do make special appearances once in a while? Very sad, as she said since the county took over, they've upgraded and replaced things but were at odds with the Gator Boys inspired Gator saving techniques and ideology? So, they boys and girls of the Gator Boys don't come by very often anymore? I was devastated to hear this and after visiting this wonderful site many times per year until last year when I had some personal issues, I went back and found this out and this was probably my last visit to this once incredible institution!! I love that they rescue and remove nuisance gators or unwanted ones from neighborhood areas and keep them safe to help and hopefully improve our ecosystem in the much needed and endearing Everglades? So, if you want to see a great show and a very nice Airboat tour albeit minus the Gator Boys of old please visit but if you're like me and want to see or meet the old Gator Boys forget it because although when yo contact them they will tell you the Gator boys are almost always there it is their version I guess they are referring to and not the real "Boys" of old. So, Classify me "Disappointed" at best!

data.title: Poorly organized money-making scheme
data.content: I’m a bit surprised by the number of positive reviews here. My experience might have been tarnished by the crowds present when we went, but there are things that could have been done by this company to make it so much better. Purchasing our passes here from Trip Advisor several weeks in advance, I mistakenly thought we’d be able to walk in, scan our passes, and jump on an airboat. Instead, when we got there, we discovered a line snaking out of the building and enmeshing itself in a line for the alligator show. Confusion was everywhere. I’m really not sure why they don’t assign you a time window for arrival so that everyone doesn’t come at the same time (which is what might have happened in my case). Furthermore, when after about an hour we finally did get to the ticket window, we discovered a huge part of the slowdown was the pen and paper signatures for liability etc. Why wasn’t this an option online when we made our purchases weeks prior? This would have saved so much time and frustration. I felt like I probably hadn’t even needed to buy my tickets in advance. Lastly, we brought our own water bottles, but discovered there was no place to refill them. This area is hot, and when I asked a staff member if there was a drinking fountain, he said there wasn’t and that the sink water in the bathrooms wasn’t safe to drink. So we were stuck paying $3 per small bottle of water at the little store (where prices are not marked on anything and there is only one overworked employee handling everyone’s purchases).On a positive note, my kids enjoyed seeing some alligators on the airboat tour when it finally happened, but by then they were soured enough on the experience that it just didn’t seem very worth it.

data.title: Learning about the Everglades
data.content: Holiday Park is right at the edge of the Everglades. Over the years the park has changed. It used to be a meeting place on Sunday for all the bikers, that is the motorcycle riders. We would gather there before forming groups that would ride through Highway 27 to other destinations like Snake Road or Lake Okeechobee, for a nice long Sunday ride.Then a few years ago, it truly became a State Park, and bikers had to move across the street to the gas station facing the park entrance. It's still not a very quiet place: Holiday Park is the start of airboat rides for tourists and it's also the best place to learn about the Everglades.There you will learn how wild animals including our famous alligator live in this hot and humid area of Florida. And for those who want, camping is available with all the commodities. It's a must to visit while staying in South Florida.
