data.title: Everglades - sneak peak
data.content: We took their 1hr airboat ride followed by the gator show. The airboat ride is informative and our tour guide, Kathy(?), was super cool and funny. All of us, including my 8 year old son, enjoyed her company.The tours start at a good frequency (one every 15 mins), so, there is no wait time. Also, the boats are not over crowded. Each family gets at least one side seat.The ride itself is enjoyable. The title actually summarizes the experience, a sneak peak into everglades. It does not take you deep into the everglades reserve. Most of the ride stays within a couple of miles from the starting point. But, you get to experience little bit of this unique ecosystem, get some basic information and get a bit of speeding airboat experience with some "drifting".We did see a couple of gators on the ride, a few birds and were informed about the sawgrass.The Gator Show (15 mins) was funny, informative and had little thrill. They also let you take a picture with you holding a baby gator for $5 extra. My son did enjoy the close encounter with the baby gator and its a good photo op.Overall, it is a good introduction to Everglades at a reasonable price. They do have a store and a sandwich shop onsite, so, you can grab some food before or after the ride/show.

data.title: Great "Old Florida" experience!
data.content: We had to stay overnight in Fort Lauderdale after a cruise, and needed something to do in the afternoon with three kids who were coming off their first cruise (and therefore used to something new and great everyday!)  We saw the ad for Everglades Holiday Park in the local South Florida guide which had a coupon for $3 off adults and $2 off children (who must be 11 and under)The place was packed when we pulled up, full of locals for the fishing and tourists for the taking.  The cost for our family of five was $75 (with coupons, tax, and oldest daughter was considered an adult) for both the one hour airboat tour and the alligator "wrestling" show.  Have just come off a cruise, this was one cheap shore excursion (think of it this way, it was $15 pp).  To add to the shore excursion feel of the place, they even took our photo before the tour and offered it for sale for $10 when we returned (we did buy it, it was great looking and $10 5x7 plus a keychain...i.e. we forgot the camera at the hotel!!)The tour was with an old-salt "I live in the Everglades" guide who was awesome.  We learned "a bunch of factual useless stuff" about the Everglades, enjoyed whipping through the Glades at high speeds and saw three adult alligators, one three year old and one baby less than a foot long.  In addition, we learned about and saw native birds, exotic species and iguanas (big four footers up in the trees!)  Our guide made sure everyone got to see the gators we came across.  Our older daughter, who is highy skeptical of everything, actually enjoyed the tour (red letter day).The alligator demostration afterwards was short, informative and pure old florida tourist trap at its finest.  We absolutely loved it, and tipped generously.This is not for everyone--but for family fun and a nostalgic trip back to the touristy Florida of the fities/sixties that I could share with my kids--well worth it!

data.title: Way fun airboat ride, and a gator boy!
data.content: My sister lives in Florida, and I've been talking about the Gator Boys for years. So we stopped at Everglades Holiday Park on our way from Key West to Fort Myers. Yippee!I wasn't all that excited for the air boat tour, but it was super fun. The boats are configured to reduce noise from the engines and boats weren't overloaded to ensure everyone had a good view. Our captain (I think it was Michael K) was entertaining and had lots of great stories to tell about the glades and gators. We saw 5 gators on our tour, which was good considering that cold weather was moving in and the gators were moving out. And the "high speed" straight away areas were exhilarating. After the air boat tour was the alligator show. We were lucky enough to have Paul Bedard of Gator Boys fame as the alligator wrangler. He was funny, talented with Carl the alligator, and dedicated to saving those amazing creatures. He also was so patient with fans, talking to us after the show and taking photos with everyone who asked (including me).

data.title: Disappointment in the Everglades
data.content: My family were big fans of the TV show Gator Boys so we drove 5 hours each way to fit this attraction into our holiday plans.  We expected the alligator rescue area to be larger and to talk more about problems with alligator/human co-habitation problems.  The area where the 'show' was is not easily accessible to anyone with mobility problems.  We were cramped into a small area (for the crowd size) and there was no protection from the sun. data.title: Definitely not for a Florida Native.  For tourists,  this place will live up to expectations
data.content: I guess the biggest disappointment is that I've been in Florida for 6 years.  I go fishing all the time.  The sights,  wildlife and food are all a part of everyday life.  I was hoping for something to WOW me,  learn something new.  It's definitely geared towards those from out of state.  Being a big fan of the show,  I was hoping to see my favorite guys doing their work.  I did not.  That's the bigges draw to that place! Again,  disappointing.  They do have some of the best,  covered airboats around for the tours however,  definitely making that a stand out feature from other tours.  The guides do know what they are talking about.  The gift shop and mini restaurant do offer good products at reasonable prices.  The frog legs are delicious,  especially with the buffalo ranch sauce.  I love my gator and my frog legs and these guys did not disappoint.  Overall,  if you're visiting from out of state,  it's a place to visit,  maybe catch a glimpse of the TV show stars.  If you have lived in Florida for any length of time,  it's a place to just stop by and go fishing or launch your boat at.  Personally,  if you want to get up close and personal with wildlife and have a blast while going fishing,  I'd highly recommend adding Lake Okeechobee to your itinerary and take an airboat tour with Big O Airboat Tours or a fishing guide trip with any of the captains out of Clewiston for some mega bass fishing.  Not taking away from Everglades Holiday Park,  because of you like that,  you'll love this as well.  Have fun,  be safe and don't leave home without sunscreen and mosquito spray!

data.title: You’ll have fun
data.content: We called ahead because our son had to meet the GatorBoys. If you didn’t know this already Paul Bedard is the only cast member that actually works there. I think one of the part time assistants to Paul, Chris, also works at the park but as far as stars of the show there is only Paul. The advertisement is a little misleading because you think you’ll meet the whole gang, not. If you want to see Paul you need to call ahead and find out what days he is there. Our airboat ride was underwhelming, we blame the weather not the Captain. The parking lot is flooded and they have a lot of construction so don’t expect to see some grandiose park, it looks like it’s in shambles. Then came the main attraction, Paul from the GatorBoys. Paul was personable, funny, goofy, and surprisingly nice. If I was rating just Paul I would have given this 5 stars but I had to consider the entire experience. Paul’s show wasn’t just geared to the kiddos, there was entertainment value for the adults too. Adult beverages are available for purchase. Still think the area for the gators appeared too small but it was comforting to hear Paul considers them part of his family. We loved his walk the dog trick. At the end of the show we got a picture of the whole family with Paul.,We enjoyed our visit and would definitely go back.Any word on when the GatorBoys will be back on the air?

data.title: Gator Boys and conservation
data.content: Took this tour from my hotel in Fort Lauderdale - picked up and dropped back so it was super convenient. Loved the airboat ride and the skipper was really good at making sure we knew what we were looking at - alligators, birds, flora, iguanas etc - and explained the history behind the waterways. Back at the Park itself we were given a show by a Gator Boy who explained the philosophy behind the conservation and rescue of alligators as well as the life cycle and habits of alligators. There's a small souvenir shop and you can get food and drink too. The Gator Boys show is done by volunteers so if you go make sure you give them a donation to help fund their work with Florida's gators. The trip from the hotel took about 45 minutes each way and a DVD of Gator Boys' shows was played - mesmerising!

data.title: Tourist Trap
data.content: My instincts before visiting EHP were that it was probably a tourist trap capitalizing on the success of "Gator Boys". But we decided to come, based on the tripadvisor reviews of the "wonderful" and "thrilling" and "awesome" airboat rides. I should have trusted my instincts. The place is filthy, and the area around the restrooms, "cafe" and alligator pit stinks to high heaven. If you are looking for a thrill ride thru the Everglades on a real airboat, you won't get it here. What you will get is a very large, covered boat that crams in 25 people; most of whom are stuck in the middle of the boat and can't see much of anything. I was lucky to get a side seat, but the rest of my party were in the middle. The front of the boat is enclosed by a filthy, barely transparent windshield. We had two very short spurts of "racing through the swamps" which was fun, but extremely brief. Most of the hour was spent creeping through the glades "searching" for gators. We saw 3.  They were in the exact place our captain said they would be before we got there...like they were planted there. We saw some beautiful birds, again, exactly where Capt Don said they would be.  I guess if you have small children, this might be a thrill for them. Our boat had only adults, and by the looks on everyone's faces they were as bored as we were.   Do some research.  Find a real airboat experience. This is not it.

data.title: A last minute trip ended up being informative and entertaining
data.content: We needed to kill time after debarkation before our flights back home. Booked the Everglades Holiday Park tour with transport to MIA through the ship. We were met at the port by a representative who stored our luggage and directed us to the air conditioned bus used to transport us to Everglades Holiday Park. The driver told us facts about Miami and the Everglades during our 30 minute ride to the park. Driver kept our personal items locked in the van and stayed on site with us during the excursion so that was helpful. Extremely hot day and not many shaded areas in the park to keep cool so that was difficult. Water (and food) was overly priced so bring your own if you can! Never been on an air boat so that was great fun and the captain was very knowledgeable about the Everglades and definately kept us entertained! Saw several alligators, iguanas and other wildlife. My teen daughter was a bit disappointed that we didn't see more but we can't control mother nature! After the air boat ride we watched a presentation featuring Animal Planet's "Gator Boys". Not sure what I was expecting to see but the show was lackluster - possibly due to the extreme heat that day - the 'gator wasn't co-operating! Did learn quite a bit from the Gator Boys and he included a lot of humor in his "act". Shortly after that, we were taken to MIA. I would probably give this tour a second chance and go again but it would be in weather that wasn't so hot. I will say, on a good note, there were no mosquitos at the time.

data.title: Amazing!!!
data.content: This trip to Florida was a "bucket list"/early birthday trip for me. I love alligators and seeing them in the everglades is something I have always wanted to do. Everglades Holiday Park was everything I could have hoped for. We started the day with the animal encounter. Emily was amazing and took the time to explain each animal and you could tell she was passionate about her work. We got to hold Oreo the alligator, Luna the albino alligator (my favorite), a snake and got to pet a skunk and Floyd the pig! I could have spent all day with these animals! The pictures they take and include are so fun to show to friends and family. Next we did the airboat ride. I knew there was a chance we may not see any gators but we got to see 6!!!! 1 kept circling the boat and another popped up right next to me! We also got to see various types of birds and a huge iguana in a tree. Our tour guide was Mark and he was awesome! He was very knowledgeable and so much fun. The everglades were beautiful! Finally was the gator show. The interaction with the gators was so fun to watch and we learned a lot. I can not say enough good things about Everglade Holiday Park and can not wait to go back!!

data.title: Captain Cody's Holiday Tour!
data.content: My girlfriend and I traveled down to the Everglades after someone recommended Gator Park (*TERRIBLE*) for us to take an air boat ride. We got up early, made the trek down south, and arrived to a mass of children, foreigners, and individuals more concerned with bug spray than gators. We were corralled into a air boat like cattle and paraded through a 20 minute loop in which we saw more air boats than wild life. We were lucky enough to see one tiny gator on our return trip to the dock, otherwise an entire waste of time and money. Following my disgust of this experience, we immediately Google searched for another location. We were fortunate enough to discover Everglades Holiday Park. We bought tickets on the smart phone en route, arrived to a dock house with a community feel, and were welcomed warmly by all staff we encountered. We purchased two beers and two gator koozies (for much cheaper than expected) and waited 10 minutes for our air boat ride to start. When our boat was called, we went down and met Captain Cody. This man was a fourth generation Floridian and had been a boat captain since he was 18, including years with the Coast Guard. This guy looked the part of an Everglade expert and it was obvious we were going to learn a lot, as if he was a rough leather bound book with the most elegant text to ever grace your eyes. Before fully shoving off from the dock, he educated us on the birds drying their wings on the buoys and used his eagle eyes to spot a massive gator in the distance beyond our air boat access. Already infinitely better than Gator Park. Throughout our entire trip, we saw at least six gators, an iguana, a beautiful hawk, vultures, and colorful fish. It helps when your tour is an hour long like it was here, compared to the measly 20 minutes at the previous park...Now I want to single out Captain Cody for a couple different reasons. This guy was the bomb. He was comical, knowledgeable, and humble, touching on all the essential characteristics of a tour guide. Beyond the obviously impressive wildlife of the Everglades, there is an incredible history to the area. Captain Cody was on top of all of the topics without missing a beat. We learned how the Everglades and canals came to be what they are today, how the Seminole Native Americans used to land to survive, incredible facts about the plant life in the area, and how human influence has introduced multiple species of plants (thanks to some genius scientist!) and animals (don't release your snakes into the wild!) into this fragile estate.Overall, this can certainly fall under the area of "another Everglades air boat tour" however thanks to Captain Cody it was certainly an event we will both remember for the rest of our lives. We can't wait for round two with the Captain!

data.content: We saw the Everglades through the eyes of a Floridian who seems to have these stunning rivers running through his veins. What an experience! Captain Swamp Thing guided us through the beautiful Everglades teaching us about the flora and fauna and telling us stories about his life in this unique area. His alligator calls drew the large reptiles to our boat(we saw a ton up close!), his love for the wildlife had the sweetest family of birds that he's been tracking practically on the boat, and his knowledge of the plant life and history of the area fascinated all of us. I can't recommend the tour with Captain Swamp Thing enough. He seems to embody everything unique and special about the Everglades.

data.title: Bitten by boat tour!
data.content: In route to the Keys, passed the quick turn-off at sign saying "Everglades Holiday Park", decided to do an "airboat" tour, after an attractive family gave us a thumbs up.Paid $64.66 total for me & my two kids to go. Ticket showed "Everglades Holiday Park Airboat Tour Ticket.  Bridges Everglades, LLC". The place was fairly busy.During our wait we grabbed lunch from their grill. The grill girl was quite rude. She didn't want to cook certain items as "it would take too long". Low quality products as the fried shrimp were frozen prebreaded, boxed shrimp. (this was one of those "too long to cook" items). Hot dogs, hamburgers, & fries were marginal. Did not get the gator bites. And watch for the black birds who will snatch your food from you in seconds!We were given Capt. Dan for our boat tour. (Ticket operator said all tours were basically the same). These are not open boats with the big fan, but roofed boats with open sides,. The captain sits on the back up high (with the fans), while the passengers sit at water level (so not the elevated view you'd expect).Capt Dan was a longtime capt there as he gave us an exhaustive history of himself and a few (questionable) near death experiences he said he had there. Nice guy, but  the boat never got over 10 miles per hour and rarely did it go any length. Tour took us geographically out of sight of, but not very far from the docks. 90% of the time we drifted looking at one or two alligators. (I've seen more and larger on a golf course)! Capt Dan seemed to think he was a bird whisperer and took us on what seemed to be his routine stops. He never, never stopped talking to us, but also talking to the birds. He'd find one or two birds here and there and say, that's Girtrude, or some other name as if he had some special connection. We were to be impressed I guess about that, as well as that he said these birds follow him where ever he goes. We saw 3 varieties of birds (mainly black birds) & some fish below lilly pads. My guess is that the black birds follow him b/c the boat barely goes anywhere from A to B to C to D, so its quite easy for the birds to follow (and they know they'll get fed). Again no high speeds, no thrilling, white knuckle zoom through Everglades you'd expect, and very little travel distance. Most of the time the engine is off (likely to not burn much fuel) and the boat is working itself in somewhat a circle between mangrove seperations and the eventual return dock.My 6 and 9 year olds (and myself) were bored from the start and their grumbling about the sluggishness, heat (from sitting under a metal roof with little movement),  and low energy of the tour only made it more painful to endure. With no choice, we "rode it out", got back to land and wished we'd never wasted out time, only then to get stuck in bumper to bumper rush hour traffic through the outskirts of Miami or Ft. Lauderdale heading dowd toward the Keys!Never again. Once bitten.

data.title: Fun experience but wish there was more to see and do.....
data.content: Our visit included an air boat ride and a gator show hosted by Paul from the Gator Boys. The air boat ride was fun, especially when our driver stopped to feed popcorn to the birds. He also let us try feeding them, which resulted in several birds landing on our arms, so cool. The driver made several attempts to locate a real life gator while we were riding around but no luck, kind of disappointing but it happens. After the ride, we went to the show, which did have quite a number of gators to see. Being a fan of Gator Boys, we were very excited to see Paul in real life. He put on a great show albeit some of the jokes he could of done without - sarcastic much. After the show we got a chance to take a photo with Paul. The disappointment came after this was said and done - there was nothing left to see or do except for the gift shop. Wish there was more to this experience especially since we drove quite a distance from Miami Beach to get there. Perhaps an interactive museum that features all of the variety of species that reside in the Everglades.

data.title: Hoping for more

data.title: Swamp Ride!
data.content: This is the best way to view the real Everglades, A big canopy covered, fast airboat takes a group of 20 or so into the far reaches of the wild Everglades. The guide takes you up close to wildlife sightings. He points out plants of interest, and explains the purpose and uses of them in this environment. It is an hour tour of a pristine, and uninhabited area that not many people will ever see. Upon return to the dock, a photo is taken of you at the boat. At this point, you walk to the Alligator Pit area, where there are many Alligators to see. A professional Alligator handler then exhibits one on one association with the Alligators for all to see. He gives a lesson in Alligator behavior, habitat, and what they do there at the park to keep them healthy. This is the basis for the GATOR BOYS TV SHOW. It is a fun, exciting attraction for all ages.

data.title: Well worth the money!
data.content: This was the first thing we did on this trip and it was absolutely an excellent start. We did the air boat tour followed by the gator show which is hosted by the Discovery channel's gator boys. The air boat tour is HOT in June so make sure to bring water and be prepared to just accept the heat. Our boat captain was named Jay and he was very knowledgeable about the Everglades and the swamp in general. While on the trio we got to see three alligators as well as quite a few vultures and birds that are indigenous to the area. The entire trip lasted about an hour and probably did not go outside of a square mile area. But don't worry, plenty to see and learn. The gator show was fun but was all the same trick you see people doing with gators. Not saying the tricks aren't dangerous or easy, just saying I had seen them all before. All in all this is a tour I would likely do again given the chance.

data.title: Very enjoyable and interesting
data.content: We had chance to do this Everglades tour while in Fort Lauderdale.  Thankful that we did.   We were picked up from our hotel and taken to their site.   That was a plus as we would have gotten lost.  🥴.  Then we were treated like royalty from that point on. The air boats were amazing and exciting ( I could have done that all day) but bring ear protection if you go.  The area is full of wildlife and The alligators were mostly in hiding as it was windy but we did see a couple. data.title: Mid-grade easy experience
data.content: Very commercial with too many airboats (almost on top of each other) on the water.  This place is a pure tourist trap at a value price.  If you’re looking for an authentic experience, avoid this place.  If you want to go on your own schedule (no reservations required) and want the quick and family friendly Everglades/Alligator experience, this is a decent stop.  The family thought it was okay, but none of us thought it was anything special.  The boats are very loud and the captain uses a scratchy speaker to try and guide you through the tour.  It was hard to hear but we did see some gators and birds.  Overall, it is an inexpensive choice for a mid-grade gator experience.

data.title: We enjoyed it - tacky tourist trap and all!
data.content: We were there Dec. 29, 2007 and had a great time!  It was one of those experiences where we couldn't quite tell if it was authentic or tacky or just tacky enough to be authentic -- doesn't matter though, we really enjoyed ourselves.  Right down to the gruff paranoid-drunk-sounding-conspiracy-theory type of guide - it was perfect old school south Florida, whether it was real or not, who cares?  We (2 adults, 2 kids aged 11 and 8) enjoyed the airboat ride a great deal and yes, we saw birds, a huge iguana, and alligators too.  I couldn't quite tell if it was an act that the guide was surprised to see so many alligators, or if there were plants that were there all the time, but again, we were on holiday and it was fun.  It is quite beautiful out there.  The facility itself is a dump - but again, I think that is part of the old school allure - hand painted signs and kind of crumbling looking.  If it were a fancy new outpost it wouldn't quite work. Anyways, we definitely recommend it for a fun experience, especially with kids.

data.title: Awesome Tour......but.....
data.content: First I want to say that this was an awesome tour.  Our guide was a pro with the boat and showed us a ton of wild life.  We were really lucky to see 4 gators, a mating pair and then 2 solo gators.   They knew where they were, and they communicated to other captains to try and see more.   She was funny, she joked and made us laugh, it was a great ride.   The but......This place has the potential to turn into a frustration for people on a timeline, or for people that don't like to wait.   No where on their website does it explain to people (probably for a reason) that any bus tour that shows up will get on boats immediately, no matter how long anyone else has been waiting.  We were there at 8:45am to make sure we had a number 1 ticket, and we thought we were good to go - then 5 mega buses show up.  We were then informed that they take priority and that we were more then welcome to wait at the tables, or stand in line behind them. Thankfully the boats filled up fast, but we we still waited an hour before we even got on to a boat.   The boats are large, they hold close to 20 people sometimes, though they really try not to stick people in the middle where you cant really see anything.  I felt really bad for the people dead center with 2 people on either side - you can't really see, you can't take pictures - it's a horrible place to sit if you want to see any of that.  They should have not made the boats that big.  And don't think it's over either - the bus people get priority during the gator shows as well.  We were tired of waiting, so we left without seeing the show.  It's a bit smaller then we thought it would be since they are the "Gator Boys" but all in all, it was a really fun experience.  We will do it again with our kids, but this time we will know that we will be in for a wait and not get so frustrated.

This 1 aligator didn't submirge, take off, only floated around in a small area, all the time the air boat engine was roaring and  switching from left side viewing to right side viewing, there was also another air boat in front of ours at the same spot and 2 more lined up behind us. data.title: Touristy spot...
data.content: I was disappointed by the fact that we felt it was a bit of a rip off to get picked up from our hotel and get charged 62$ including taxes and not seeing any alligators on that day in the glades. I know and I am aware that this is the beauty of nature however I still think it's over priced if you get picked up. We've been asked by our driver (Rafael) yesterday on our way back to the hotel to add 15% gratuities that were forgotten to be charged by the Manager and we did not give it to him of course... A gratuity is not a must and if it was, it should have been added to the bill that we paid. How can you forget that? It's clearly up to the customers to tip we feel like it but there is not such things of charging 15% of the big to get gratuities. Imagine how much would have been that trip? It's sad to see that tourists are seen as wallets when traveling and this way it was disgustingly done...The "Show" on that day wasn't a proper show... The pipe did brake so there was no water for the aligators and all of us were expecting a proper show which would 'WOW' us but this did not happen unfortunately.The staff and the driver (Rafael) is very friendly except 1 or 2 girls wearing brown shorts and an orange jacket... They kinda scream and expedite people when the tour is over, seems like clearly just interested in the money?... Quite sad!! I wonder where does the 10 and 15$ goes to whenever we take a picture with a snake or a baby alligator?? I sincerely hope this money goes to their food and veterinary fees!!The information provided were very good and informative so thank you for that!I was expecting with my dear fellow colleagues to have a different experience and see quite a few aligators in the nature but this is out of anyone's hands I believe however it would have been a different experience if we were pushed to feel that money plays a big role in this tourist adventure... data.title: Alligators Up Close
data.content: Great experience. We selected this company as it was closest to us, economical and did not need reservations. The airboat ride was wonderful. They are renovating the spot, as they should, but the the renovation was very loud. So while we waited for about 20 minutes we were unable to talk. it was interesting to watch though.The ride was about an hour and Jimbo, our captain, was great. We saw osprey, an iguana, about 5 alligators, cranes, tons of birds and learned about the Everglades. Jimbo circled each animal so both sides could see it and then moved on to provide the least amount of trauma to the animal. I appreciate that. The boat was covered and it rained a bit and we were dry. Birds kept landing on the top. We were out of the sun and the airboat was quieter - as some others on the boat mentioned this was different than other rides. Although we couldn’t look forward as a result, we missed nothing. The alligators were CLOSE, AKA within 1 foot of the boat.There were 14 people on the boat so we could slide from side to side to see things. He mentioned that sometimes there are 26 on the boat. We then went to see the show. It was a bit different with only 14 in the audience that can hold up to 250, but it was interesting nonetheless. A little cheesy at points, but he was personable and informative.With the tips for the airboat ride and the show, both mentioning this was their only source of income, the experience was pricier than anticipated.

Don't miss this on your next visit. I would tell you more but.... just check it out.

data.title: OK day in mass transportation
data.content: We had a fun time on the boat with Swampy Jay. We got to see gators and a good bit of Everglades wildlife. Our guide was really entertaining, and gave us really good information on the wildelife.You do not however really go into the glades. You go on some wide man made canals with large airboats. They have many boats, so you have 3-5 boats in view the whole time. On the good side there is always boats going, and you do not have to book or wait in line. In the mid of summer the roof on the boats to keep you in the shade for the 60 minute trip is a big plus. For a first time look at the Everglades this is a nice place to go, but next time, I'm going with someone who can take me deeper into the swamp(river) on a more exclusive trip.

data.title: You have to go
data.content: I brought our family of 7, 3 adults and 4 kids (14,12,10,9) for the Everglades airboat tour and we all loved it. I had been before, and enjoyed it so I thought the kids really would. The airboat itself is cool. I wish I could rip around on it! Our guide, Doug, is the longest working guide there, and funny enough he was my guide when I was there 8 years ago too! He has quite a keen eye and really knows his nature. We were fortunate enough to see 4 alligators and lots of other animals. It being out in nature, there is no guarantee you will see anything but we were very lucky!The ‘show’ after the boat ride was a lot of fun for the kids. The gentleman preforming was very personable and good at what he does. You could tell he genuinely cares about his alligators. The little enclosure made me a little sad, seemed kind of dingy and old and small. These gators were HUGE. Our tour included two free pictures, but they had an albino gator that you could hold with another baby gator for another $20. Gulp. But I did it and the kids were happy. Then of course you can get magnets or key chains ... Your free pictures can really add up. But when are they ever going to get to hold another albino alligator again?! If you’re near the Everglades, go for a tour. It’s cool and safe and fun.

data.title: Wonderful Day!
data.content: We have been to Everglades Holiday Park several time now since the Gator Boys show came on Animal Planet. We have been driving to the Keys since the 70,s and never knew about this Park until the show. The airboat ride ride was awesome! The Captains are knowledgeable and funny and will stop every where for you to see some little thing!!  The animal and bird life is incredible! The Gator show is crazy!!  These guys (and girls) are completely committed to these animals! You will have a new respect for these amazing animals when you leave the park! 2 things to mention. The crowds start pretty early in the day so the best time is to go about 9 or 10 in the morning if you can. Also you can buy your tickets on their website and you won't have to wait in THAT line. Also the tickets online are $5 cheaper! There is no date to use specified you you can use them anytime.  Have fun!!!!!

data.title: Easy airboat ride
data.content: Some of the positive aspects of this airboat ride facility are that it is easily accessible from Fort Lauderdale, and there are frequent rides so there is not a need to book in advance. We went here after we couldn’t get on at Big Swamp. It was busy, but there were plenty of boats in operation and we didn’t have to wait very long. Plus, it is a bit less expensive than other local operators. The boats are covered, which offers protection from the sun but on the other hand does detract from the airboat “wind in the hair” experience. Also, it was crowded on the circuit, with one boat after another, so we didn’t get the feeling is solitude that I’ve experienced on other airboat rides. It would be good if they provided ear defenders, as the boat engines are rather noisy. The guide, captain mike, was knowledgeable and enthusiastic, providing a good commentary and answering any questions. We did see a few gators and birds, which was fun, and the short gator wrestling show afterwards was quite entertaining. This was good, but there are other tours that offer a better experience.

data.title: A little WILD makes for a fun time!
data.content: This is especially fun for out of state guests.  The simple WILD of the Everglades is new and different.  The Air Boat ride, with a knowledgeable guide makes for an interesting and fun 30 minutes. If you get Capt. Chuck, you'll be well informed, as well as entertained. All three times we've been there, a 'gator' has come right up to the boat, nose to hull.  Great photo op.  The rest of the park has 2 or 3 short informative 'shows' that provide a lot of information about the native animals that have been rescued, and now reside in the park.  You even get to hold baby alligators.  One of the things I love about this park is that the staff truly care about the animals.  This isn't a 'job' to them, it's an opportunity to care for these creatures; everything from boa's to panthers to owls, to "Cannibal" the daddy-gator, that calls this park home.  If you want to see the glades, hear the stories, and see the animals up close, this is the place.  There's a snack shack with drinks and hot or cold snacks, including gator bites;  a well stocked gift store, and a very helpful and friendly staff.

data.title: One of the better airboat deals around
data.content: At $34 per adult and $22 per child (ages 3-11), this place isn't cheap. However, it's one of the better deals around as the hour-long airboat ride also comes with a short 15 minute show and 2 free printed photos with a baby alligator. The airboat ride is fun. This is one of the only places I've seen where the airboats are actually covered, providing some shade on those super sunny days. The boats seat up to around 20 people though. So, they could get crowded and you may not get a great seat on the side for prime gator viewing.On our trip, we saw one gator in the first 40 minutes and then another 8 in the remaining 20 minutes. Our captain, Rocky, was personable enough though he heavily favored the left side of the boat where he sat, and folks on the right side got very little opportunity to get up close and personal with the gators. In addition to alligators, we also saw ospreys, iguanas, an armadillo, egrets, and other birds.The show was okay - definitely not the highlight of the visit, but a reasonably entertaining talk where you learn more about alligators and their rescue program.

data.title: Awesome experience
data.content: I have been on airboat rides where the only goal was to spin you around, but this was different. The air boat ride was the perfect balance of thrills and learning about the nature of the Everglades. The ride went fast at times with no spinning. We would then stop to look at birds, plants and alligators. Our guide was knowledgeable and funny. He made us think that he was going to " break the rules", but he didn't. After the ride, we saw a show with one of the swamp boys. He dangerously wrestled alligators, even sticking his chin in an alligator's mouth. There were other things to do here like renting boats or fishing off the docks. There was also a place to get food like alligator meat.

data.title: Meet the "Gator Boys" and get a longer ride than most.
data.content: I've been on airboat rides before and seen several gator shows.  This wasn't the fanciest gator show I've seen, but it had one of the "Gator Boys" from the TV Show.  He gave a lot of explanation that I hadn't heard before, so it was informative and fun to watch.  He let us know how truly dangerous it could be, even if the gators seemed quiet and non-aggressive. And I got a photo with a "Gator Boy!"The boat ride was longer than usual and we saw several gators and got up-close to a few.  We saw lots of different birds, some very large. Our guide did a great job explaining the encroaching water lilies, things you can do with cattails and other fun facts.  It was very enjoyable.We had the VIP tour which included a shuttle from our hotel to the park.  I found that the driver was one of my favorite parts of the trip.  He was very friendly and told us a lot about the park, Everglades, and Miami in general. He recommended a few restaurants, which we were happy to visit.I'm not sure what would have made this a 5 star tour for me; maybe more to do at the park than the boat ride and a short show. It seemed like it took longer to get there and back than it did to take the tour.

data.title: Fun little diversion
data.content: The park was much smaller (and more crowded!) than I expected.  Overall, it was a mildly entertaining way to spend 1-2 hours.  You wouldn't want to stay there longer.  In a nutshell, you buy a ticket for an airboat ride through the Everglades.  You then wait for them to call your ticket number (we waited for 15-20 minutes).  You get on a boat with about 15-20 people.  Together, you spend an hour seeing alligators swimming alongside you, native birds, and learn about the local foliage.  Interesting stuff, and certainly worth an hour's ride.Then, and only after the boat ride, can you see the alligator show.  This wasn't really what I expected in that it's not much of a show.  You line up down a long area and stand to watch a guy get in a fenced off area with a dozen alligators.  He chooses one of them, hold the alligator's mouth open, then closed, then open, then closed, then puts his head against the teeth... all while cracking jokes and saying how dangerous this is (which I believe).  The entire "show" lasts about 10 minutes (maybe less).  I kept thinking it was the pre-show or something, until we were filed out when it was over.Overall, it's a little park, with a small gift shop, a place to line up for your airboat ride and a little (as in not long) alligator show.  However, it was an interesting experience for a change of pace from the beach.  If you have a day where you don't know what else to do, it's worth an hour or two of your time.

data.content: Well organized in managing large crowds.  You are assigned a group number which is called when you board the airboat so you don't have to stand in line very long.  It would have been nice if the small children were seated up front for ease of viewing but the captain did try to rotate the boat so all could take pictures of the gators and birds.  I do think ear protection is helpful for small children as our little ones complained, but you will have to bring your own.  The gator show is fun though short.  You will get hit up for tips by both boat captain and at gator show so bring cash.  The little ones really liked holding the baby gator at the end although you do have to wait in line for that.   All in all, a good experience that is memorable for the children.

The alligators were too hot, so they were at the bottom. We did see 2, but my 4 1/2 year old barely saw them. The show was a joke. Some very young man who claims to be an alligator wrestler tried to make some really dumb jokes and he opened the alligator's mouth, put his face on it while open and pretty much just talked about alligators. It wasn't all that informative and it was NOT entertaining. The BEST part of this was when we got to hold a baby alligator and have our picture taken. That lasted all of 30 seconds. The entire time we were there, the operators and show people were asking for tips. We purchased tickets online. When we arrived, the cashier tried to up sell us into an animal encounter with a skunk, pig, snake, tortise and something else. Online it was something like $69. She said that they had deeply cut the rate and it was $20, but one of us had to be with our daughter - well of course we do. We had to PAY FOR THAT! Really? In the end, don't bother wasting your time or money. There's nothing to see and it's ridiculously hot there (not much place to take cover from the sun).

data.title: Fantastic Time
data.content: We did the Airboat Ride, The Alligator Rescue Show, and the Animal Encounter.  Our favorite was the Animal Encounter.  We got up close with a young alligator, a (de-scented) skunk, a raccoon, a tortoise, and a pig.  Each was a rescue of some type.  The package also included pictures taken on a nice camera, several prints, and all the digital copies.  It prevented people from going picture crazy with the animals and let us focus on the experience.  The Airboat ride was great. The airboat driver was fun and offered good info and humor.  He found two gators for us, two iguanas, and several other small wildlife.  Bring a jacket.The Alligator Rescue Show was fun.  Lots of humor while remaining kid friendly.  Easy and safe to get up close to these apex predators.  Overall, 5 stars.  Bring cash for tips, as the airboat driver and gator presenter are volunteers who work for tips.

data.title: Yeah, we saw a few alligators.....let us make it up to you”
data.content: Hi gang,   Upon debarkation from the RCCL Majesty of The Seas following a weeklong cruise to Key West and Havana, Cuba we were supposed to be picked up for a visit to Everglades Holiday Park soon after de-boarding.  Thru a scheduling/communication snafu we were picked up nearly 1 1/2 hrs late.    Our tour incl a 60 min airboat tour with narration.  Very loud engines, narration was cheesy at best but we did see 3 -  6 ft alligators and a baby (18 in long).  The airboat pilot knew just where to look.  Temps about 88 deg with Florida humidity, water depth was 2-3 ft mostly.  After the airboat ride we were shuttled to the alligator show where a former “Gator Boy” TV star played with a coupla gators, cracked jokes and then said, “shows over, don’t forget to contribute”.   Stood in line longer than the show lasted....Not much shade sitting in the bleachers and glad to go.  Photo ops with Burmese python, albino gator and a “you-can-hold-the 2 ft croc” photo op.     No sooner had we ordered our food (gator bites (8 pcs, dice sized) and fries ($11.95) we were told by the shuttle driver that we had to leave NOW......    That obviously doesn’t bode well, a coupla of us ate our lunch on the 30 min drive to the BW Airport hotel.    Very bad organization, remember they were 1 1/2 hrs late picking us up at the ship ??  So now we have to leave because they’ve got other parties to pick up ????    Hot, humid day, ok boat ride, boring alligator show, overpriced theme park food, not allowed time to eat said lunch.....I wasn’t  over-wowed by the experience.        If you’re interested in seeing alligators in their natural habitat but don’t expect anything beyond theme-park mentality, this might be your must see.   After an hour and a half delay, no priority “lunch is on us” or partial refund offers, we were just left amongst the masses. Rich

data.title: Very Disappointing Day
data.content: We called in to take a one hour air boat ride and the subsequent gator show today, September 18 2016. The boat ride was so disappointing as it was advertised as a one hour ride but the time spent at any speed would not have been more than 3 minutes. The rest of the time was spent floating around watching small gators and pointing out birds and grasses. We expected to at least be motoring at speed for half the time but it could have been done in a punt with a 10hp outboard. data.content: We felt we had to go for an airboat ride while in Florida, so we  chose this provider due to location. data.content: I came here while I had a day to kill in Ft Lauderdale between flights to Mexico.  It was much better than I expected.  We went on the Everglades boat tour, which was about an hour. I have always wanted to ride in one, since I have seen them in movies and TV they look so cool.....Also learned that they have little John Boats for rent at the location, and next time I am in the area I want to check those out...maybe do a little fishing in the everglades. Prob the funniest part was before the guy sticks his head in the gators mouth he said "this is where a degree in Criminal Justice got him"! Also they help rehome the gators caught by trappers- who would normally kill them for their skins etc, and for a few bucks donation to their fund you can get your picture taken with the little gator.This was also easy to find, and not far from the Main rd, so was a great way to see the Everglades!

data.title: Tourist trap
data.content: I really wanted to go on a boat ride through the Everglades during our anniversary trip to Fort Lauderdale. Everglades Holiday Park was well-rated here on TripAdvisor, so I bought tickets online and off we went. It was a windy day, and our guide did warn us that alligators preferred calm water. The boat held more than 20 people, and we were crammed in like sardines. Seriously, we were in the 2nd row, and I could not sit straight because of knee room (I'm 5-9). The front windshield was so dirty and scratched that it gave zero visibility. The guide was very knowledgeable, and he was diligent in trying to find us gators. We saw 2--one hiding under a tree where the water was calm, and another swimming in the open. We thought that we'd get to drive fast--we did, but only for about  2 minutes of the 45 minute tour. The gator show at the end was fine. We did appreciate that the park is a sanctuary for gators that would otherwise be destroyed.Best tips: go when the wind and water are calm. And temper your expectations.

data.title: AMAZING JULY 4TH RIDE_CAPTAIN "BABY-FACE" ERIC
data.content: We're locals living in Davie but wanted to do something a little different for July 4th, since we weren't headed to a family bbq or fireworks (our relatives live out of state). The airboat ride was a perfect way to pass time mid-day. Although it was very sunny out, because the boat has a covered roof and the day was breezy, we were pretty comfortable.  Captain Eric is a great host, very knowledgeable about local wildlife, from native to invasive species (and fish to fowl). We were able to see several alligators and for the first time a female eating! I've been to several of the alligator theme parks in South Florida but this was honestly the best. The hour just flew by and I really appreciated how our Captain was so attentive and patient with everyone's questions. We were in a mixed group of different age ranges/nationalities, and our Captain was just as interested in talking to the adults as the kids. I'm especially proud to be a Floridian when I see tourists having a good experience and being treated well-after all, our state relies heavily on the presence and generosity of tourism!All in all, it was time well spent, and the free photo at the end a nice touch. I'd like to add the the other staff at the park are really patient and customer service oriented,  which was impressive considering there were literally hundreds of people there at the park coming from tour buses. We arrived as the tour buses were leaving, but it was still organized considering the volume.

data.title: You will see a Gator BUT .......
data.content: We were traveling with another couple who wanted to do an airboat ride in the Everglades. Not sure this met the criteria but it was okay.   We got to this off the Turnpike (about 10 miles).  This place is on a canal and has airboat rides up until 4:20 PM in Dec. Probably based on when sunset happens.  Ride was approximately 1 hour.  Cost was $23.50 per adult.  Some folks had coupons but not sure where they got them.  Boats are covered and have a plexigalss front so pictures are only from sides.  Boat drivers are your guides and do attempt to turn boats so both sides can take any pictures they want. I would say in total we road less than 2 miles on the canals. I have included pictures that show what you will mostly see - grasses and a lily pad type flower plant growing in the water.  The rides do speed up at times but don't think you will be ripping along. The driver turns the boat from side to side to make it seem fun. Boat engines are from Cadillacs and these boats looked homemade, not what you think it will be.  We saw several gators, 4-7 species of birds, iguanas, and various vegetation.  Guides were knowledgable on plants, etc.  Boats have about six rows of seats and ours had people in about 4 rows and were not crowded but seated by number in party with some parties taking 2 rows. Children on the boat seemed entertained.  They do take a group picture before you leave and try to sell it to you.  They have a take out  window that sells gator bites that we did not buy.  There appears to a camp ground on site but were not camping and I do not know details.  Other people did come up and put boats (more like what you expect if you watched Miami CSI) into the water from the ramp located beside the ramp your boat leaves from.  I think was an okay experience and I did not choose this but let others in my party choose.  They wanted a boat ride and they got it but stated it wasn't as fast as they thought it would be. Women's room had 3 stalls but only one flushed.  2 stalls had been used by people knowing that it didn't flush.  I think that tells you something. Prior to the ride they give you a "Gator Show".  It is a young man in a fenced area with bout 8 alligators.  He uses only one and shows how to open the mouth and talks about the line of sight a gator has and demonstrates how he uses this to handle the gator.  For $10 you can sit on a gator and get your picture made by your friends and for $5 you can hold a baby gator.  I was not impressed.

data.title: Fun, Educational Trip
data.content: Was pleasantly surprised. Very much enjoyed our airboat captain. He was knowledgeable and demonstrated on more than one occasion how you can survive if you find yourself stranded in the Everglades. Also provided some great insight to the various birds, reptiles, etc. that inhabit the Glades, how the gators live, what they eat, etc. Would have loved to gone out on one of the smaller airboats, but the bigger ones get up and move once they get underway...ton of fun. Probably could have done without the Gator show afterward (it's part of your ticket package), but the young guy that got into the cage with the gators did a nice job and performed a couple of stunts I wouldn't want any piece of so kudos to him!Found the staff to be very accommodating / friendly. It's an easy drive from Lauderdale and surrounding areas. Overall, it's a trip worth taking.

data.title: So much potential, but experience comes up short
data.content: We bought the tickets online and got in line at noon on Friday. We anticipated that the wait would be an hour or so. We ended up staying in line for 2 hours and 40 minutes in the sun to check in for wrist bands and get on a boat. It was exhausting for adults not to mention how boring it was for kids to wait in line for that long. This business has so much potential to be fun and entertaining for its visitors during the whole duration of being at the Everglades Holiday Park, but Park is a strong word for this experience. The boat ride was ok. We saw 3-4 alligators and a bunch of vultures, which was cool. I don't know if all captains do the same information routine, but I thought we could have learned more during our 1-hour tour. The alligator show was entertaining. The humor was more for adults than for the kids, but we enjoyed it. I definitely would not do it again until they make improvements to the park experience.

data.title: overrated and Disappointed
data.content: we spent the day in the everglades and after reading the reviews of this park we drove out from Fort Lauderdale to check it out , It is by far the most well advertised park and so is the most well known and is the park that most ticket booths / ticket sellers seem to sell tours toFor that reason it is VERY busy with coach loads of people pulling up often ,we found it to be to busy for our liking ,the place isn't all that big , on top of that it seemed to be over priced for what I would call pretty poor attractions , the Airboats are some of the poorest I have seen , the seats are all on the same level , with a covered roof and seat 6 or more deep , meaning that only people on the outside stand any chance of seeing anything , The area that the boats went in seemed poor and not that large a area , lacking in wildlife The Alligator show again was very poor, in a very small area , I would much sooner see a wild  Alligator then a captive one , and just up the road at shark valley you can do just that for a fraction of the cost It seemed to me that this was the first "park" on the highway form both Miami or Fort Lauderdale and so was the most quickest and convenient park to ship paying guests to If you drive right past this park you past many other more little parks that also offer Airboat Rides , most on a REAL airboat and most don't have the big crowds , if you keep on driving 30 minutes past you will come to shark Valley national park , just $5 to enter you will see dozens of 5ft to 6ft Alligators (in the winter months) right within walking distance , you can take a tram tour for the same cost of a Airboat Ride and I can guarantee you will see much more REAL wildlife  my advise if you are driving is , drive on right past MUCH better to be found further past this park , REAL airboats , smaller ones not geared around fitting as many paying guests as they can onto a boat , if your going to pay to ride a Airboat at least ride a real one , drive to a smaller park that appreciates your custom more , keep on driving to Shark Valley and you will not be disappointed , it will then make you realize just how poor this park is

data.title: Sensational Experience for All Ages
data.content: The show was amazing!!!  And unlike one negative reviewer who said they had to pay $60 for five people to watch the show is total BS. THE ALLIGATOR SHOW IS FREE! If you want to take a airboat tour then you must pay for that, of course. Since I was with my elderly mother who is terrified of water and my beloved Chihuahua, we skipped the airboat ride. With my Chihuahua safely inside her stroller we stood right next to the fence while Chris Gillette put on a fabulous show.  At the end he took a few questions and stated that donations are not required but welcomed. They did ask for a donation for getting your photo taken with a baby gator. I believe it was only a few dollars. Of course, my mother loved that and got a great photo with "Sponge Bob". He wasn't tiny but probably 3 feet long. I can't recall but I think Chris said he was 2 years old. Not sure. That was in 2013. Sponge Bob is probably now huge and not privy to selfies but he was that day.  The photo opportunity was well worth it. Sponge Bob was so sweet he even fell asleep. :-) The care and love for the alligators is truly apparent here. As a 20+ year vegan and diehard lover of animals. I am always watching for any sign of abuse or neglect when I am out and about. The people who have created this alligator rescue are amazing. The care and attention they provide the gators is what you'd expect in a 5-star hotel.  Rescues like this deserve all the donations they can get. They depend on donations to continue. It's not cheap to feed an alligator and they have many! Plus, vet care, equipment, transportation, etc. all costs money and lots of it. They bring in injured or sick gators rehabilitate them and release them back into the wild. Some are unable to be released for various reasons thus, have a life long home at the rescue, being treated like a king or queen. Alligators have a bad reputation and shouldn't. They're amazing creatures and if you've never been up close to one then you must. Alligators are living dinosaurs and deserve our help and attention just as any other animal. Donating to the Gator Boys Alligator Rescue is tax deductible. The more you give the more you can deduct. Always, say no to items made from alligator skins or body parts.  Save an alligator from being skinned alive for ugly handbags, boots, and belts or from being served in a restaurant. Keep them in the wild and keep rescues like this one alive and doing whatever they can to protect the beautiful and powerful alligator. Please donate and tell others. I recorded the show and posted it on Vimeo.  On Vimeo search for the exact phrase with hyphen,  Gator Boys - Alligator Show

data.title: Broke boat
data.content: We went on 3/1/2015 on advice of our son and daughter in law  who went late last year,  I was excited to take a ride on a  fast airboat and talked my wife into going,  we were first in line and on the boat sitting up front,  our captain. ..captain Mike. ..was funny and really pumped up everyone on our boat about the  BIG CADILLAC 500 ENGINES...the hold on to your hats speech etc . etc etc.  As we were ready for our 1st run down the  "SPEED" LANE he gunned it and off we went, picking up speed but it sure didn't seem so fast and something just sounded wrong,  soon we slowed down and captain Mike said something went wrong with an engine and he was going to try to fix it, after messing around with it for a while he said his boss was bringing out another boat, 20 minutes from breakdown his boss showed up with parts to fix the problem,  turns out 1 engine threw a belt so no power to the prop. Ok boats fixed, time for the speed lane with both engines working fine right  ?? Wrong, same engine threw the new belt so we continued on at snails pace, saw 2 gators,  lots of birds and countless other airboats from their place racing down the speed lanes at full power, Bottom line for us, we expected to have the ride we paid for,  a little speed and excitement mixed in with slow search for gators, we got half....we still enjoyed our visit and would recommend this place but it just wasn't our day on our first trip to Fort Lauderdale .

data.title: The worse guide ever
data.content: This was my second airboat tour and first for my family.  Holiday Park is not what we hoped for at all. The trip was completely ruined by our tour boat Capt. Rick or Rich.  He did nothing but talk about himself and his experiences for an hour.  We came to Holiday Park to have a fun ride and learn about the Everglades.  Well, all we kept hearing about was Capt. Rick's 43 years in the Everglades and "his back yard" as he would say.  When the airboat was moving things were OK.  But once we stopped we knew we were about to hear from Capt. All About Me.  Unfortunately he likes to talk so we spent more time stopped then moving.  His constant rambling about himself became uncomfortable and disturbing.  He even when as far as to say the other Captains in company followed him and that he trained them all.  God I hope not. Based on other reviews I can see that this isn't true. If you get Capt. Rick/Rich(?), go to the end of the line and wait for another boat.  He was awful and we will never go back or recommend this company to anyone. I was so disappointed that this guy ruined my families first experience on an airboat.    Other things you should know.  Due to the Gator Boys show this place is packed and the lines are long.  The gator show is 5 min tops, with limited educational value. The airboats have roofs so you miss out on half the experience of riding in an AIR boat,  you don't get to feel the air.  Bad Call Holiday Park.  Yes, you'll stay dry in a Thunderstorm but isn't experiencing the elements part of the adventure?   Finally, the Everglades Holiday Park operates in a canal region of the Everglades.  You don't feel like your in the everglades at all.  It's more like a boat ride in a marsh lands along any east coast river.  My suggestions is to try Sawgrass Recreation Park up the road about 10-15 minutes.  Open boats and educated guides who talk about the Everglades, not themselves. They also provide a show and even have numerous other critters to see and learn about.  Sorry about the bad review but I wouldn't recommend this place over the others in the area.

data.title: An exciting educational family tour of the Everglades Ecosystem with caveats!
data.content: We took our two 6 & 7 year old grandchildren on the tour and alligator show on an overcast, slightly rainy Monday when the pool was not an option. The park is easy to find with GPS and close by Ft. Lauderdale. There's ample parking and the site is well run and organized. Adult admissions are $15 each, Children's tickets purchased on Groupon were $13.25 each,but buy them on the Holiday park website and they're only $11 per child. Our total cost for 2 adults and 2 children was $52! After purchasing tickets wait by the docks on benches under shaded sun ports for your number to be called. Have a friend take your family picture because the park guides take them and will be happy to sell you an 8 x 10" for $10 after you exit the boat ride.We declined them since we took our own. Really with everyone bringing cameras and cameraphones this is a lame, anarchronistic moneymaking stunt. We were at the front of the line and were able to sit in the front row. Since it was raining the visibility out the plexiglass windshield was limited there was ample viewing out the sides. The driver constantly turns the boat so port and starboard passengers get good views. There are many photo ops. Just set your camera vibration control "on."  Our guide, Rich, was very funny and a wealth of knowledge about the history and wildlife in the ecosystem. As an adult I found the tour educational and enjoyable. My grand kids loved it too. The older girl had already studied alligators in school so this field trip was a valuable field experience. The tour was one hour long. After about 40 minutes the similar views become tiresome. We did not see that much wildlife; two alligators, groups of vultures, an egret, and some grackles, starlings, and iridescent peahens that came to the boat to be fed popcorn.The driver guns the engines on three occasions and the boat flies on plane with the front off the water! The noise is deafening.  Bring ear plugs.This ride trumps one on a roller coaster. There was a two year old girl behind us who was so frightened she cried the entire ride. I would rate this attraction appropriate for ages 5 and up. At the end of the ride our driver Rich made his pitch for tips by announcing: "We work for tips so if you enjoyed my tour any tips would be greatly appreciated." I thought this was a venal act and resented him shaming guests into giving gratuities. Yes, he did earn it but I don't need to be prodded to fork over the dollars. Gratuities are earned and people will respond if they desire to do so. Broward County or whoever runs the park should be responsible for seeing that their are adequately reimbursed. I know FL is a "right to work state." Are these drivers not paid as stated? Shame on Broward County. We left the boat, declined the $10 photo, and lined up for the alligator show by the "Gator Boys." Be forewarned...stand in front or wait for the next show or you will not get a place where your children can see the show. We were at the end of the line. You don't want to be here if you bring young children. When the crowd was admitted all the adults ran to grab all the positions along the fence. There is a 4 ft. high wall in the pit and then protective fencing above that. No tiered seating exists as in Seaworld Miami. Our grandchildren has no place to stand and view the show so I had to hold my 6 year old grandaughter on my shoulders which was temporary. The "Gator Boys" need to be trained in audience control. A simple "Adults, please step back and permit the younger shorter children to stand in front so they can see the show." The adults there were selfish and no one volunteered to let the children move in front of them. There were over a dozen huge protected alligators inside that the kids could not see. We got frustrated and left early. Afterwards we ate the picnic lunch we brought. There are ample picnic tables under sunports for sitting and eating, as are outdoor clean bathrooms. Bring a picnic lunch, leave it in the car which you park below the decks, and eat an enjoyable meal. There are food and drinks available but you can save $$$$ bringing your own drinks and food. The park admissions are expensive enough without having to buy food for a family of six or more. Want to see more? Don't miss the Shark Valley trip. Many more alligators seen close up or from the observation tower. Take a bike tour or a tram ride tour.

data.title: Best Nature Tour of South Florida
data.content: I have taken several friends to this attraction. It never fails to impress. There is something about seeing live gators in their natural habitat that makes people's jaws drop. Of course it is humid, of course it is usually hot, of course it is usually a sunny day when you want to go. The boats you are on are large and safe with bench seating. (Ok for some sitting on a metal bench seat may not be the most comfortable thing in the world, so if inclined, bring a seat pad.) The boats do have a roof, so you are not baking in the hot sun, and are shaded. Of course if it rains you are also protected, at least from above. Of course the sides are open air so you have better views. The trip on the boat is perhaps 1/2 hour or 45 min. It is a fast paced trip with other tour guides getting on their radio and telling your boat captain where the gators can be seen, so it's very rare that you don't see a gator. There is gator show and explanation by the workers who are also TV stars in their own right on the nature and travel channels on TV, if you have ever seen "Swamp People" or "Gator Boys", this is the place they work! They do offer AAA discounts and I have seen coupons around town for discounts in addition to being in the Entertainment Book, so look for them. The savings can be great for this great trip!

That's my only complaint, didn't really know when the next show was and we waited in the hot sun with no shade. It would have been nice to know a schedule for the shows. Either way, the show was enjoyable. Kevin was funny and entraining. I guess I should say, brave, as well. Be warned, the park is currently under constitution, but the future of the park looks great!

data.title: FUN, FUN, FUN
data.content: Capt. Rick has been running boats in the Everglades Park for 14 years.  His stories leave you spellbound while viewing the beautiful Everglades National Park.  This is the second time I have attended this attraction, the first being 4/2014 and had the pleasure of meeting Capt. Mike who has been in the Everglades boat system for as many years.  He was most pleasant and described a lot of the scenery and animals we encountered along the wayNow Capt. Rick has a female friend, an alligator, who responds to his voice and boat when in the area.  She in turn "protects" the Capt. from any other alligator that she deems unfriendly.  The Capt. protects her from any other boats going too fast thru her area so she won't get hurt or hit.  They are quite a pair.  She came out while we were there and swam around the boat close enough to photograph.The tour was great with Capt. Rick because he scoots the boat to go sideways so you get a breeze and see the entire area 360 degrees.  Lots of wind stirred up.Children get a kick out of the trip and I advise anyone living or visiting South Florida to make time to spend a day at the National Everglades Park off Griffin Road West.You also get to see the Gator Boys from tv wrestle the gators in the fenced in area.  This time I got to hold a baby alligator in my arms.  Big Thrill!!!Visited September 2014

data.title: Fantastic Morning!
data.content: I have to admit I was a little leary of going to this place.  But, I wanted an airboat ride and a chance encounter with a gator, I was terrified and exhilarated at the chance of this happening! I was not disappointed at all. We boarded our boat with Capt. Rocky a very nice man, friendly and happy. We headed out on our quest for the gator. He took us through a few long stretches of water at a faster speed, which was enjoyable, than slowed down to look for the thing that I am Terrified of .. a Gator. First stop, no luck, second stop no luck. Then it was gator time! We ended up seeing 4 Gators. At each sighting Rocky would manuver the boat so everyone saw the gator and got plenty of pictures. He also took us to see a family of purple gallinule birds. It was obvious Rocky enjoys his job, his  enthusiasm was contagious.We returned to the dock and we were treated to a great show by Chris as he handled one of the rescue Gators. Chris was very funny and extremely knowledgeable, excellent presentation! Overall, we had a 5 star experience, everyone was friendly and nice. And as an added bonus they give a generous discount to veterans, what a great place!

data.title: Fun place
data.content: I have lived in this area for about 30 years and had never been to Everglades Holiday Park until last year when my Sister came for a visit and one of the things her husband wanted to do was see some gators. They take you out in the swamps on an airboat for about an hour. They have names for the gators and when they call them they seem to appear out of nowhere. It really is amazing since they are not allowed to feed them. I have no idea what makes them come out when they are called but it was amazing. There is someone that takes your picture before you get on the boat and it was a nice souvenior to have of your visit there. There is also an alligator wrestling show after the boat tour and a shop where you can buy food, sunscreen etc.

value.text: gators should be in a rescue sanctuary

data.title: Doesn't need to be all inclusive
data.content: The airboat through the everglades is a great day out. The photo should be optional and the gator wrestling should be shut down. How cruel to have a dozen gators all crammed in that space, no water and being harassed all day long for a fake show. Nothing short of animal cruelty. The gators should be in a rescue sanctuary like they have at Flaming Gardens. This show needs PETA to shut them down.

data.title: Way better than I thought
data.content: I must admit I really didn't want to go BUT I am so glad that I did. I have a blast. We started out with an airboat ride thru the everglades. It was gorgeous out (went on the first ride of the day), it was just getting warm, the animals were just waking up. We stopped to look at the alligators and we fed  the birds popcorn and one landed on my hand to eat. After the boat ride we went to the alligator show. I felt bad for them but after they explained the history of "alligator wrestling"  I felt better and the fact they are rescue gators from people who thought they could have made pets out of them made me feel better. This is a must!

data.title: Alligators and Educational- A Must See!
data.content: Highly recommend this as a must see spot in Fort Lauderdale. We did the airboat trip, animal encounter, and talk with the Gator Boys. Our Captain was hilarious and made the entire time in the boat enjoyable on top of the beauty. We saw many alligators and they take the time to make sure everyone gets a good look, the Everglades are beautiful, and the many different kinds of birds were unreal. There is a lot of educational information given too, between the Captain giving us interesting tidbits on the birds, trees, and of course alligators, and then the short informational show with the Gator Boys, and learning even more about just how smart these alligators are. They are updating and expanding their location, so it will only get better.

data.title: Really cool, especially for out-of-towners
data.content: I took my sister and her two kids (ages five and six) here when they visited from Illinois. They were so in awe of just about everything. We only saw two gators that day (I've seen many more other times I've come here), but our guide was so good at telling us about all the other things that go on in the Everglades. Nobody felt like we missed out on anything.  I highly recommend the airboat tour; it's just a really cool experience. The alligator show is pretty lame...my niece and nephew were not impressed by that at all. But getting to hold a baby gator and have their picture taken with it after the show was totally worthwhile, and that was included in our ticket price. Definitely a fun event for people of all ages.

data.title: Fun for the Whole Family at great value.
data.content: This was a fun trip for the whole family.  My Dad is 83 and he had fun on the Airboat ride.  The ride was very steady and fun.  My son is 10 and he love seeing all the natural habitat (birds, plants etc)  of the Everglades and the Gator boy show.  The cost of ticket include the Airboat ride (1 hour long with 3 short straight speed run) & the Gator boys show (20 mins) afterward.  I went about 1:30 pm and saw 3 gators during the 1 hour ride. P.S. : You should get the tickets online at their website as it is 23.50 vs 27.56 at the park. (you can get e-ticket but still need to redeem at the main ticket building ).  The tour operator said better to do the tour early day/afternoon as less gators as it get cooler after 3pm.Please vote helpful if info help.

data.title: a worthwhile tourist trap
data.content: If you're a family, I'd say this is a worthwhile tourist trap. Pro: easy drive from Fort Lauderdale, free parking, priced well ($23/ticket, $10 for a picture/keychain, $5 to take pic with baby alligator, decently priced souvenirs and food), two shows filmed here so you may recognize, airboat ride was fun with a very friendly, funny and personable guideCon: these guys hustle and you'll be reminded that they work for tips after the boat ride, then again at the alligator show and then again when you take the pic with the alligator. It's also quite stinky inside.

data.title: Kids will love it!
data.content: Having some time after a cruise we took this excursion. There is an alligator demonstration with the handler, which I give him a lot of credit for getting so close to these gators. Then you head over to the boats for a ride thru the glades. I was thinking we're going to fly thru the everglades in those fan boats you see on TV but instead it's more a leisurely fan boat that holds approx. 15 - 20  people. And it's a short ride. But kids will love it. Unfortunately we didn't see any gators but it's a fun thing to experience. Being we went in November the weather was perfect. There is a place to buy snacks and lots of restrooms.

data.title: Captain Chaos was AMAZING
data.content: My husband and I were looking forward to this part of the trip.  It was our last day of vacation and we ended with a bang.  It was a beautiful day.  The airboat ride on Looney with Captain Choas was exciting,  fun,  and educational.  He was a hoot! They call him the gator whisperer. We saw 7 gators that day!  I noticed one person complain that you don't go very far in the boats,  but why would you need to, the everglades/gators are right there.  The show after the air boat ride was also very fun.  The 2 pictures they take of you then print for you, which are included with the package are a nice add on for a momento. The cafe was very good.  We had the gator bites basket.  Fishing is allowed down there as well.  You can fish off of the dock or put your own boat in. They were catching a lot of oscar while we were there.  Overall great experience,  and I would definitely recommend.  Also request Captain Choas!

data.title: Get there early for a great time.
data.content: Went with Everglades Holiday Park for the airboat ride early August and had a great time. We were told to get there early in the morning since the gators don't come out much when its hot later in day. Got there right at 9:30 and we saw between 8-10 alligators (a couple may have been repeats) and we really enjoyed the show afterwards. Also saw a bunch of other wildlife with several species of birds. Wasn't very long but the volunteer Chris was excellent. He's doing research on alligators so enjoyed all the facts he was able to teach us. Sad it is run on a shoestring budget with the airboat captain having to beg for tips since he's paid only minimum wage and volunteers not paid to do the show afterwards.
