data.title: A Great Educational Fan Boat Ride and Alligator Show
data.content: To get our first taste of the Everglades, we took the fan boat tour at Everglades Holiday Park. Our captain was both humorous and informative, making for an extremely enjoyable experience. It was our first experience on a fan boat, and I would definitely recommend some pre-trip Dramamine to anyone who gets motion sickness easily. The slow swerves at high speeds and general spinning of the boat for both  sides to get great views left me lightheaded by the end. We did see 2 alligators on our tour, along with several vultures, "sea chickens," and an ibis, so we got a pretty good spectrum of the wildlife and plant life in the glades.The alligator show afterword was also informative and humorous (and at times a bit scary!). I wouldn't be so nonchalant around do many gators, but the show guide was a well-versed trapper and educator and alligators and it was interesting to watch his tricks in grabbing a gator along with learning of his rescues and protection of the species. I would definitely recommend this trip to anyone looking for a good first glimpse of the Everglades.

data.title: You get your money's worth - FOR SURE.  Very affordable for families too.
data.content: This was an excellent place for families.  Very economical as well.  Drinks are $1.50, beers are $2, chips are $.75.   They also have a cafe on site serving hot dogs, burgers and gator bites.  The airboat tour is cool.  We didn't have to make reservations.   We bought out tickets and only waited about 15 min for the next boat.  They fit 20-25 on each boat.  Thru take your picture before you get on the boat.  Make it count because the picture is actually free.  Yes, FREE!  They don't try to lure you in to buying it.  They just hand it to you in a cute little frame when you come back from your tour.  Try to sit on the end so you can see.  The boats have covers so that helps with the sun but it does kinda hinder your view if you are in the middle.  Boat feels very safe, even when going fast.  Saw a few gators in the water.  Once you are done with the tour you get a free alligator show sponsored by the gator boys from Animal Planet.   After that you get the opportunity to hold a baby gator for only $5.  Well worth it.

data.title: We saw some sleepy alligators
data.content: This is an affordable, family friendly way to learn something about the everglades and see some alligators. The airboats are large - 20-30+ passengers - and stay in pretty open areas. The tour guide did a good job and was careful to turn the boat around so everyone could see. We saw some interesting birds and 3 sleeping alligators and were surprised to learn there are about 2 million gators in Florida.An airboat ride we took years ago had only about 7 passengers and went deeper into the everglades and we saw much more than this time, but it would be considerably more expensive.We didn't stay for the free gator show afterwards.

data.title: Great idea to do this!
data.content: Fun airboat tour. Approximately one hour in length ($28.50 adult). Pickup at most hotels. PCheck online before going for discount opportunities examples AAA & AARP. The drive from Fort Lauderdale (approx. 30 minutes) to the park serves as a great prep for the tour. There were numerous alligators (8-9) throughout our boat ride. Birds and numerous iguanas also. The Gator Boys of Animal Planet are based in this park. Following the tour there is a gator show with one of the volunteers. Actually one of the 'nuisance' gators had just been brought in by the team for us to see. Great adventure for young and old. Concern for the wellbeing of these animals is felt throughout the tour. One free group picture comes with package. Nice gift shop on property. Plenty of bathrooms . Advise doing in the morning and apply bug spray.

data.title: Gators, glades, birds and airboats fun!
data.content: The Everglades Holiday Park Airboat is a fun experience. We have been on airboats before in the everglades national forest west of Miami and although this area is not as vast, it is a good time and they do a good job. There are alligators and they move the airboats to both sides so all can see and take pictures, many species of birds and they do some fun speed runs for thrills. The gator show is not wrestling, like rolling around, but more of handling the big guys. Still very interesting and included in the $25 list price - we paid $21. If you paid full price, you didn't pick up one of the many free books at any hotel/gas station/drug store that has their coupon for a $4 discount per person. Chris, one of the Gator Boys did the show and stays outside before/after the show and is great about taking photos with you. They also have a baby alligator for $5 donation picture. Remember, they are ALL volunteers, so yes they work for tips, but they don't hound for them. tip jars are there, but not being stuck under your nose. A fun place, good time and worth it and very informative. Hint, look for the peacocks by the white bridge.

The boats are covered which is a plus on a rainy day like we had. They made sure everyone could see everything by swinging the boat around a lot. All staff were friendly. The bad: the boats are too big. I prefer a smaller operator. We didn't learn quite as much as I'd have liked. Too big an operation for my liking.

We pulled up at the same time as 8 tour buses, and they had reserved their times so we had to wait for all of them to take their boat tours first (the facility handled this pretty well and had us see the Gator show first, and also had many boats running, which helped move things along).We enjoyed ourselves and would recommend. data.title: Got to see some 'wildlife' great first time visit!
data.content: Got to learn some about the life in the everglades and experience it by getting right close to it all! Not sure how 'wild' the wild life is as it seems that possibly the gators and birds are tamed but living in their natural habitat.  I wondered if they were being 'treated' with some goodies when arriving to their supposed location as the guide's hand went under the boat to tap and get attention.  Still, for me, if that is what it takes to get me and other newcomers to learn about life in the everglades and see the local animals, I'm fine with it!  I enjoyed the experience and learned a lot! I also went to another place up north more along the coast and learned other different things about the gators, so I can't say it was an inclusive sharing of info but good enough for me to enjoy for my first time! I'd enjoy it again as well! It went over the mentioned 2 hours it would be, and left me feeling I got my money's worth but glad I was not on a tight schedule. Also enjoyed the gator show afterward, while short, it was it's own thing and a good addition.  Our tour guide definitely had his own style and added to the trip.  And while a 'tough' guy with life's experiences, he was definitely very caring about giving tips to get in and out of the boat, and helpful to those with knee issues.  People of all ages and variety of abilities were on our tour, including myself recovering from knee surgery.  Bring water, as you will likely want it during the excursion, and remember to use the restroom before you go on your tour.  We did not get tickets ahead of time and did not have to wait long.  Seems they close around 5, so definitely plan to go before evening. You can get some unique (to me) food, gator and frog legs, but do it before the grill closes.  We enjoyed some fun (Mexican style?) popsicles, coconut cream, yum!  Their workers were friendly and helpful and a gift shop with a variety of items you might want for souvenirs.

data.title: The highlight of our vacation!
data.content: We went to holiday park last week on our week long Florida vacation.  I have a 7, 6, & 4 year old.  We decided to skip a day an expensive day disney and see real florida instead.  So happy with our decision!  We started off with doing the "Animal Encounter" with our guide Emily.  She was the best, so patient and sweet with my curious kids.  We got to see and hold a gator, a sweet snake, a chocolate skunk (soooo cute!), and meet the cutest fox I have ever seen.  I paid the extra $10 to get all the pictures on a USB since you cannot get your own pictures, they will take them all for you (worth it!).  Emily took excellent pictures!  I don't know who liked this experience more my kids or my husband and I.  It was worth every penny! Thank you Emily for such a wonderful experience!! Then we hit the airboats for an hour long ride with Al, our airboat captain.  He was friendly, informative, and you can tell how much he respects and loves the everglades.  He showed us about 5-6 gators up close, iguanas, fish, and lots of birds.  Al let my kids feed a family of Gallinules (swamp chickens).  My little kids could see everything, there was plenty of room on the boat, we all felt very safe.  After the airboat ride we went in to watch Gabby wrestle a gator.  My kids are HUGE gator boys fans, the show is one of their favorites to watch.  They loved watching this in real life.  It was like seeing a celebrity for them!  Its amazing to see such courage and respect for such misunderstood animals.  After the show we got a picture with a baby gator.  The park is run really well, easy to navigate, and a must see!

data.title: Going down; down; down!
data.content: OMG what a disappointment! As locals since 2008 we’ve taken multiple international guests to this alligator boat tour. It is becoming worse by the year. This year is the last time. So rude; loud and overbearing call to order over the loud speaker; overcharging by $80 because the cashier is so hasty; yelling at guests to remain in line as they’re trying to shelter from the rain; making guests stand in the rain until every person in the group has their photo taken. All this is happening while the staff took shelter on a covered deck. We saw quite a few alligators which was a win; but take a walk at any one of the many Everglades entry points and you’ll have a much more relaxing time; seeing as many alligators. The gator exhibition show was an improvement - the show was the same and seating was comfortable vs standing in the hot sun. To sum it up - the boat guide seemed not interested in the people nor animals; mumbled something through the speaker and steered the ‘what could be an exiting airboat ride’ into disappointment.

data.title: Unique South Florida Experience
data.content: I have been taking friends lovers and visitors to holiday Park for 20 years. I've been there by myself. While Florida's national park lacks the grandeur of the mountains and forests generally thought of when evoking national parks images - its river of grass is a magical wonder that for many requires focus to appreciate. Unfortunately, too many Floridians are transplants and never appreciate the unique swamp that is the " real" authentic original Florida.   Give your self a treat - bring your camera.  Take an airboat ride.  Unfortunately, Broward county took over the park which had been privately run by a colorful gang of rednecks for eons - but, a recent trip proved that they had not totally sucked the regional flavor out of the place.  I do miss the old redneck swamp men who used to run the boats - their bombast and colorful language their personal slant on swamp preservation is missed.  The bland county employees reading their script is pale fare.  But the river of grass is majestic in its subtle beauty - you cant take that away from her.  And you can still hv a beer and alligator bites while you wait for boat queue.

data.title: Disappointed and saddened
data.content: I was visiting with 2 family members. I have previously tried airboat rides (with other airboat tour establishments) and had been really excited about these and wanted my family members to also have this nice experience. However, we were so very disappointed about our experience here. The type of airboat felt like being squeezed into a can. There was very limited visibility as it was not possible to look out of the plastik 'window' in the front of the boat and there was very limited views to both sides when sitting in the middle of the boat. The guide primarily focused on promoting himself and not so much about sharing his (most likely high) knowledge about the Everglades and wildlife. Before the airboat ride, we saw an alligator show. There were many alligators in the same and quite small confinement. When walking around the area and seeing the anmials in the cages, we were sorry to see the conditions of the cages which were small, seemed to be lacking maintenance and gave the impression that the animal needs had not been taken into consideration. In some instances it was difficult to see the animals properly due to the condition of the 'glass'. Especially the two foxes saddened us as they did not have much space and the cage was completely bare. The foxes were pacing back and forth. Photos were taken with a baby alligator. We felt so sorry for this little creature which was placed in the hands of many, many tourists who had a photo taken with them and the baby alligator. Altogether, we were left with a very disappointed and sad impression and experience.   Based on this experience, I would like to suggest the following considerations; - Other types of airboats allowing a full view of the sights- Smaller types of airboats for face-to-face contact with the guide which would also invite for more spontaneous questions and dialogue with the guide - Improved conditions for the caged animals

data.title: Captain Tonya makes this experience great
data.content: The airboat ride was very interesting, primarily because of the knowledge of Captain Tonya.  While the animals may or may not show themselves during the trip, she worked hard to coax them out and make sure each side of the boat received ample time to take pictures and observe.  She was able to attract birds that know and trust her, and took her time to explain the most interesting items - not just your standard "script".  This is the second everglades airboat ride we've taken, with the other at another location.  In comparison, this location is much more commercial.  Pros:  more access to parking, food, restrooms, snacks, and a free group picture.  Cons:  more boats going out in short intervals, which creates more boats that you encounter during trip.  Capt. Tonya worked hard to create some separation between us and other boats to increase the likelihood that the animals would come out.  It worked - we saw a few alligators, iguana, birds and vegetation. We did not take advantage of the gator show which was part of the ticket price, as we would rather see wildlife in their natural habitat - not being asked to perform.

data.title: Nice stop during family vacation
data.content: Visited with family in January 2017.   Airboat captain was great and very knowledgeable about the wildlife and history of the Everglades.  Tour felt a little longer than it needed to be and if we didn't have other plans that day, maybe not such a big deal.  Compared to another nearby Airboat tour company, Everglades Holiday Park airboat tours are about 2x as long (hour vs. 1/2 hour).  Tips were mentioned toward the end of the ride, not pushy, just blah... not really what you want to hear after spending $50 for 1 adult and 1 child ticket.  Gator Boys Gator Show was very cool....however, the constant mentioning of "Tips are appreciated" grew old quickly.  Fun, somewhat educational show, lots of laughs from the audience, but jeez...please back a bit on the frequent requests for tips.  Focus on the show and performance and the tips will follow. *Opportunity to take pics with an Alligator and snake after the show... $10 for 1 animal or $15 for both.  Fair deal for the experience and the pic is provided.  We were ready to leave though and after the frequent push for tips, I didn't want to reach back into my pocket. Gift shop - fair pricing, gets crowded very quickly, but overall niceFood / Drinks - didn't have any, but availableRestrooms - nice mobile / trailer style setup, comfortable for being in the middle of the EvergladesRecommend this place, just know that the Airboat tour may run over an hour and the Gator Boys show is after, plan on being here about 2 hours to do both comfortably.

data.title: Florida Untamed
data.content: This nature center is around the corner from my house and I have been coming here for years  so it will always hold a place in my heart. I primarily come here to run. There is not a lot of visible wildlife compared to some of the other nature centers in the area although I have seen butterflies, raccoons, armadillos, and a really large land turtle on the grassy plains part in the way back. When you first enter you follow an elevated boardwalk to the two story visitors center. The lower level has a ranger station with some educational displays. To the left is an amphitheater with bench seating. On weekends I have seen folk concerts and weddings held here. Also on the lower level you will find the bathrooms and water fountains. The second floor is a reception area called Royal Fern Hall complete with a kitchen that can be rented for weddings and meetings. Every Halloween they do a nice program for the kiddies up there. Once a week they also offer yoga in the park. There is a sign advertising it at the entrance from Lyons Road.Once you go around the visitors center you will come to a small gate that will take you out to the paths. The path to the left is the Cypress Creek Trail. It is a half mile elevated boardwalk that loops back around to the start. This is the only good area for a wheelchair. The path to the right takes you over a small bridge and out to the back field and a path that goes through the woods. Here you will find the one mile Prairie Overlook Trail that has a small elevated covered observation platform with benches. Maps for everything are at the visitors center. If you come here you want to make absolutely sure that nothing is left visible in your car. There has been a number of break ins primarily taking place later in the day towards closing time when there are less people around. You also want to bring some bug spray with you especially if you plan on going through the woods. The last time I was here this month was not bad but I have been here when the mosquitoes were so thick I literally ran for my life. This a great and cheap (no fee) place to relax in nature and decompress from the stress of the work week.

data.title: Natural beauty hidden within an urban wilderness
data.content: This was a nice little surprise and well worth the visit. There is a lengthy boardwalk across Cypress Creek that takes you through wetlands where you can find some wildlife. There were gorgeous butterflies everywhere. After the boardwalk, you reach the point where all the trails meet. Going to the left, you eventually hit the perimeter trail. At this intersection there is a huge gopher tortoise, watch out for it! Very cool. There were also decent sized fish in the creeks on the way there too. On the perimeter trail there is a large overlook where you can see much of the park and the beautiful trees. The trail then makes a loop and you come back to the grassy path that takes you to the visitor center. You can try to then take the Maple Trail- but at your own risk! It was very muddy and narrow when I went and there was a sign saying 'increased mosquito activity'. Thankfully, at the entrance to the boardwalk section there is a shoe-wash stationBest of all, this is all FREE! Even parking was free. And I was shocked that the trails and bathrooms were so immaculately maintained and clean, considering they just work off donations. There was also a beautiful wedding taking  place at the visitor center when I was here too. Very neat!

data.content: First visit, loved the beach and had a great time, but......the $8 per vehicle admission (parking) fee-----YIKES! Next time, we'll bring a cooler with frozen ice water.On the plus side... the water was clear and azure blue. The sea floor was nice rippled sand, no rocks or hard surfaces. data.title: Great place to spend a few hours
data.content: Hollywood, Florida, is NOT like Hollywood, CA! It reminded me more of the beaches at Venice, in Los Angeles, but more polished and built up. The Broadwalk aka Boardwalk, it like the one in Venice, paved and goes on from this park southwards to nearly Jefferson St, after that, it is just beach. Whatever you do, park at the North Beach Park ( depending on the day, cost is $1.50 to 2 bucks an hour, or $15 all day. There is no attendant, so take money for the machine. You want to to walk, jog, skate from one end of the walk to the other, it is a very wide boardwalk lined with palms. Stunning. The ocean will be at least 80F. The park is one of the larger public facilities located just after Sherman st going north along the A1A or N. Ocean drive. This is where the trolley ends and then returns to Crowne Plaza near Hallandale Beach Blvd. The park has all the facilities you need to change, restroom, places to eat string the boardwalk. Because the beaches line the shore for many, many miles, this park is not crowded. For public garages, these are located at the Hollywood Beach Marriott between Carolina and Taft st. Not far from the park. There is a garage between Garfield and Connecticut St also, near a much smaller park called Charnow park, Not far and is a good walk is the beautiful Hollywood Marina it begins at Michigan st and ends at Poik st. Hollywood is only 20 miles north of Miami. You can also check out the Anne Kolb nature Center, which is across from the park on Sheridan St. If you go a little more south, there is West Lake Park where you can rent kayaks and canoes and explore the intracoastal waterway. So, this park is a good central location for these other activities. five miles down the road, north, is John Lloyd State Beach park.

data.title: Come on in, the water's fine!
data.content: The emerald-colored tide was heading out leaving behind a plethora of shells (and a few jellyfish!). A constant light breeze was kicking up some nice waves that kids of all ages were enjoying. The water, for this time of year (November), was amazingly warm. Some families were having great fun building sand castles. All was right with the world!The beach wasn't crowded at all and amazingly, no one had their tunes cranked so one could enjoy the calming ocean noises and family laughter. There are plenty of shady spots with picnic tables and a few folks were making use of the provided grilling stations.The fee to park on site is $8/day per vehicle, there's a small deck for snack bar patrons, descent rest rooms, and a shower to remove all that sand from between your toes.While the sand isn't quite as white and soft as other beaches on the East Coast of Florida, the lack of crowds, great shells, and general all-around cleanliness make up for it in spades. Oh, and there's a long, wide blacktop walkway (no motor vehicles) on the city-side of the dune, so there is ample room to hike, bike, walk, or run if you have an aversion to sand.All in all, a clean and lovely park!

data.title: Nice Natural Area
data.content: I came today to explore the area. I must have driven by here a thousand times on my way to Boca without ever thinking to stop. This 56.3 acre park sits on the land between the Atlantic Coastal Ridge and the Everglades that was subsequently drained to create Broward County. It used to be a vast marshland with pinewood flatlands on the higher elevation.  Today you can enjoy an elevated boardwalk and nature trail. Benches and restrooms are among the amenities provided. On my visit I only saw the occasional butterfly but alligators, snakes, wading birds and birds of prey have been seen in the area. You can expect to see vegetation like slash pine, saw palmetto, beautyberry, swamp and sword fern, wax myrtle, and yellowtop. Events held here include eco action day held on the fourth Saturday of the month October through May when volunteers remove invasive species of plants. There are also nature at night hikes and school group and scouting programs. Some of the events are tacked to a board by the bathrooms and a listing can also be found on the website. If you can't arrange for a guided tour you can take a self guided tour with the enaturalist which are signs along the trail with a QR code. When I snapped a picture of one it took me to a YouTube video that described the area I was in. This is another great little natural area that gets you outdoors and exercising. You might not notice it from 441 as you drive past but it is worth a visit.

data.content: We enjoyed our visit to this nature center. I don't think we paid any admission, and we were the only ones there at the time. The place looks fairly new, and it clearly was well-funded, with a beautiful & spacious building featuring a theater showing a video, clean bathrooms, high-quality walkways, and better-than-average exhibits in the nature center. There was an odd modernistic sitting area along the path dedicated to victims of something (can't remember) that seemed out of place among the fauna & flora. This site is located very close to Flamingo Gardens, which we had just visited, so these two sites made a very nice day's outing.  Overall, a pleasant stop.

data.title: Gem of a find!
data.content: What a lovely park. On the edge of the Everglades, this park has lots to offer. We visited last day of January 2019 and there was no entrance fee but it seems it's usually $1.50 per person.  There's acres and acres of space with picnic tables and grills dotted all over the park, plus shelters with picnic tables and bigger BBQ grills for larger groups. Apart from, walking, jogging, cycling, skateboarding and scootering around the miles of pathways, there are various activities available. An outdoor pool, but not open today, boating, model aircraft flying, golf, clay pigeon shooting and a firing range. We had a lovely day just chilling by the lake, watching the wildlife, and reading our books. There are clean toilet facilities. Well worth a visit.

data.title: Nice campground
data.content: We camped at Markham Park because I had a road cycling event in Ft. Lauderdale. We also brought our mountain bikes to ride on the trail at the park. The mountain bike trail at the park is very nice, however, the park charges extra, $5.00 per person, per day, to enter the mountain bike trail.  We definitely weren't happy to have to pay to use a trail inside the park since we were paying to stay at the park.  Be aware that there is a pistol/rife range and skeet shooting range next to the campground so don't plan on sleeping in. It didn't bother us and we hope to use those facilities on future trips. The campground was nicely kept.  It is not really private since anyone coming into the park as a day use can drive around through the campground.  There is no gate to keep anyone out at night.  I was told that there is a security person that makes rounds at night.  Overall, its a lovely park with lots to do. A example that other counties should use on how to attract visitors to their counties.

data.title: Nice visit
data.content: This is a great park to visit and well maintained. Amenities include bike trails, one of which is on a canal next to the Everglades, there are playgrounds for the kiddies, boat rentals, nature trail and tennis courts. The park also includes some pretty uncommon amenities also. There is a shooting range and there is also an rc airfield. I haven't visited the shooting range but the radio controlled airplane field is great, especially for the children. Here you will see many radio controlled airplanes flying and many rc enthusiasts.The park also includes a campground. The park allows for both rv and tent camping. There is also a primitive camping site. We tent camped, the site included water, electricity, and even Wi-Fi. The campground includes a bathhouse and dump station. The sites are pretty well spaced and we were lucky enough to have four of the sites next to us open. A tip, the most northern sites of the campground are the one's closest to the shooting range. Also, if you camp over the weekend be sure to stop by the Fox Observatory. Hopefully you have clear skies, the professional astronomers will let you view far off planets and galaxies.

data.title: Mosquito heaven
data.content: My husband and I along with our two boys decided to try tent camping over the New Year holiday. Bought all the gear thinking that it would be good weather and would be great; however it decided to rain the first night and it was so humid that the mosquitoes formed a virtual blanket over everything. I guess they can't do much about the mosquitoes, but I didn't appreciate stumbling across red ant hills that seemed to be all over our campsite and among the grass on the side of the road to get to the bathrooms. Speaking of the bathrooms- very poor! No air conditioning so you sweat every minute you are in there. Women's room ran out of toilet paper the first night. Second day when we took showers the women's room was OK, but in the men's room one shower only had cold water and the other was too scalding to use. We opted not to give our three year old a shower for that reason. Got woken up at the crack of dawn by the sound of gunfire from the shootingrange.I suppose if you go in a travel trailer or RV and you have your own bathroom and a couple of bikes to explore the area it probably wouldn't be too bad, but I would never recommend it for tent camping!

data.title: More to do than you think.
data.content: This place is a diamond here in South Florida. A large open area where you can do so many things. The gun range is large and very well run. There are miles of safe walking, jogging and biking trails and roads. The terrain varies and is a nice change from the rest of the area. The Camping area is spacious with lots of room between sites. The dog park is very nice. The mountain bike area is open but you have to take a course at the front office and pay a fee per year. The mountain bike trails are very challenging and for all levels of experience. They are well maintained and offer extreme variations and combinations. The trails change with the weather from erosion, so a trail is never the same twice! It is a great place to try at least once. It does get very crowded on the weekends and they have many special events and races. It gets very hot here in the summer but the fall, winter and spring are excellent.

My son really enjoyed it, even though it seems more for younger kids (my son is 14). We got the all day pass, went the early around 10am, went back to out tent for lunch &  nap, then returned again in the afternoon. I plan on going again, really enjoyed. The only thing that bothered me a little was that some people were a little loud late at night. FYI if you plan to buy things at the Walmart close by, don't do it. It's a small one & they really don't have much. They had firewood which was good.

data.title: Great Park for Families or Singles
data.content: If you are in the Deerfield area and want a break from sightseeing, Quiet Waters Park is an ideal place to spend a day. It is HUGE, over 400 acres.  There are walking paths, bicycle paths, a lake with a very cool "zip line" that whisks you along the side of the lake on water skis. In addition, there are facilities for many other activities:  canoeing, paddle boats, swimming, windsurfing, camping, picnicking, miniature golf. There have been places to purchase snack food, though I'm not certain they operate all year round.  Best check that out!  Access to the park is free during the week; I've been told there is a parking fee on weekends.  The various activities like the water-skiing do carry a fee.

data.title: Quiet Waters Camping...It's OK
data.content: My review is only about the campground, because I did not experience anything else in the park.PROS: 10-15 minutes from Deerfield BeachVery clean bathroom facilities, campground, and campsitePlatform tents (Rent-A-Tents) are convenient and have bug netting, and seem to be in good conditionCONS:Reservation process is a little difficultNot really an "outdoorsy" place, as I could see outside at night without a flashlight because the city lights were so bright.Staff: Firstly, the guy working in the office at check-in spoke so quietly and mumbled it was very hard to understand him. He seemed to be in "la la land." It was really quite awkward. Secondly, the security person who patrolled the campground at night in their vehicle must have assumed my friend and I were there illegally, because we chose a site away from the crowd. Instead of addressing this false assumption in a professional manner (as in, actually getting out of his vehicle to see our campsite pass was clearly sitting in my car's dashboard), this guy blew his horn several times and shined a spot-light at our tent at 11:30pm and again around 1am...when we were just in our tent trying to sleep!!!Thirdly, when we called the campground manager to address our issues with the security guard, she did not seem to be genuinely concerned.Other than the late-night disruption, I am moderately pleased with my experience at Quiet Waters Campground. I don't know that I would stay here again. I would only recommend it to a friend if they needed a cheap place to stay near the beach.

Our trash was never picked up until we told the maintenance people about it and said that we had to leave it in the grass which was a lie because we've seen them pick up other peoples trash from the trash can. data.title: Serene Urban Wilderness
data.content: Secret Woods is a great little spot. It's tucked away off busy 84, and once you enter, outside sounds melt away. The trails are well-maintained and relatively short. They take you through a variety of different ecosystems with good interpretive signage. I estimate it's a 30-90 minute experience. Every staffer I've met has been incredibly kind and informative. The bathrooms are nice and clean. I rarely see more than one or two small groups, so it's always peaceful and quiet. But make sure you bring your bug spray! I highly recommend sitting a spell in the butterfly garden. I've been taking my son there since he was 6 months old. Back then it was a great way to get out of the house and into uncrowded nature. These days, I spend more time chasing him down to the New River to watch for manatees.

data.title: Quiet spot, Saw Manatees, Knowledgable Staff, Close to 2 cruiseport Hotels
data.content: While staying at the Rodeway Inn post cruise trip we walked about a 5 minute walk to the entrance.  (Red Carpet Inn is also there).  Exercise care crossing the road!  Great place to view wildlife while learning about local plants.This is a nature center not a picnic/playground type park.  It has several well maintained trails, all short walks into different areas.  The New River Trail winds around among white, black and red mangrove trees to the river where we saw 5 manatees.  Beautiful!!  The red mangrove trees look like stick trees walking on water.The Butterfly garden trail is a very short walk full of plants that attract butterflies.The Laurel Oak Trail has beautiful Strangler Fig trees, one hosting a rather large wild comb of honeybees.  Has a exhibit center full of things for kids to see and touch.  Including several snakes and an active contained bee hive with and entrance in/out of the building.Has Geocaching!  Tons of fun.Kids- there is also a trail that would be great for kids of all ages.  At the beginning there is a box with a small pack of paper for them.  Then in short intervals there are etching stations.  They place their paper over a metal type sign post and with the attached metal bar they rub it over the paper and it "etches" the picture on their page.  Each one with a different plant or animal to etch into their paper book.Staff- super knowledgable and willing to assist in answering questions.  Took a nature tour with naturalist Scott, he shared history facts, interesting factoids about plants and animals.  He really knows his stuff and answered our endless questions.  Opened from 9-5, free parking, no entrance fee.Truly a secret Woods!  A must for nature lovers to take pictures and learn!  Also to pass time before/after cruising or going to the airport.Tip- long pants or bug spray was helpful to us.

data.title: criminals ruin everything
data.content: It's a shame. I live in S. Fla. many many years.   I go to Westlake.  It is more open to keep an eye on your car.  TY Park has had problems for over two years  now.  They cannot find the criminals that are smashing cars everyday. Yesterday, they were handing out leaflets to be careful.  Secret Woods is beautiful, been there a few times not lately, and now that I read this is going on there as well, that is scary.  I never never leave anything valuable in the car, but they might think you do and break in anyway.  This goes on on Hollywood Beach as well.  Broken in twice there.  It is a crying shame and I blame the parks people for not installing cameras and being more proactive with security.  You want tourists to come back and it seems like nobody gives a damn.  The police for over two years cannot stop this ring at TY Park. There is not enough police to go around for this.  I agree with one person, this place is turning into a slum that is for sure.  People can't even relax and just unwind and get away without being victimized.  It is outright disgusting. You want tourists to enjoy themselves and to come back and enjoy your surroundings,then DO SOMETHING.  ENOUGH IS ENOUGH.    I live here and am always watching, but sometimes that doesn't help either. In today's world unfortunately, you have to have eyes behind your head and always be aware.  So, when do you relax......

data.title: A great place to escape the city.
data.content: I spend my week cooped up in a classroom so on the weekend I am always on the lookout for somewhere to get some fresh air and exercise. I was in the area to get some shopping done so I decided to check out this area in the hopes of getting some fitbit steps in. There are a few parking spots and picnic tables in the lot. Before you enter the trail there is a bathroom, a feature I always appreciate. On the other side of the bathroom is a few benches set up so people can give nature talks. Before you start your walk you can download the eNaturalist Program on your phone to get a self guided tour.The entire area is 66 acres. The trail is on an elevated boardwalk over basin swamps and pine flatwood. It reminded me a lot of Fern Forest Nature Center but smaller. The trail winds through the Cypress area so you are never sure what you are going to see around the corner. There are two covered pavilions that lookout onto the natural area. There is also a small pond and waterway that runs along part of the boardwalk. I didn't see any wildlife but I was walking quickly for exercise. I find that if you want to see animals you have to really linger. Nevertheless it was a nice walk on a beautiful morning. Bird walks are held September through June and there are nature at night hikes October through May. A full schedule can be found online at Broward.org under the parks and recreation heading.

data.title: A good place for birding, but make sure that you don't go alone! Bring family and/or friends!
data.content: My advice is to not be alone, don't only do the boardwalk and hike the trail in the back, north side. I didn't like it the first two times when I limited myself to just going on the boardwalk, and thanks to a friend, found out about the other area. You can get to the hiking trail by walking out the gate, making a left turn (north) and walking all the way to the back. Then make your left and go inside and you will see the hiking trail. In this section in season and at the right time (meaning early morning or before dusk around 5:00 PM), you may see lots of warblers, butterflies, woodpeckers and maybe even the great horned owl. I was delighted to see the great horned owl and a huge flock of cedar waxwings.

data.title: Amazing Spot for Viewing Nature
data.content: I had not been to this location in many years, so I was interested in returning. I was in the area, and admission was free on non-holiday weekdays so I stopped in. I was pleasantly surprised by the amount of wildlife: the most I have ever seen at this location. In just over an hour I saw an abundance of birds (egrets, herons, ibis, wood storks, cormorants, ducks, moorhens, coots), squirrels, and lizards (anoles and iguanas). It is a nice hike around the massive lake, or just to relax under the shade of the abundant oak trees. There had recently been a tropical storm, so the lake had overflowed some areas of the park that had to be detoured around. There were unfortunately a few negatives. Upon arriving I noticed that a homeless person living in a car overflowing with junk had obstructed part of the parking lot with their vehicle and was begging for change with a large sign saying, "We may be homeless, but we are still Christian" Yet no park staff were removing this illegal panhandler. While hiking the trail up a hill, I came close to being run over by a group riding loud motorbikes on the trails and grass around the lake, despite motor vehicles being prohibited on the hiking trails. I observed an employee in a truck eventually stop them and told them more than once to leave, but were ignored and taunted. At one point the employee chased them with the truck, but I don't know why they didn't just call the police to arrest those punks. The third negative was that the shoreline all around the lake was completely littered with trash, yet I saw no employees making any effort to remove it.  Despite the negatives, I will still return, and I hope the Broward County Parks & Rec makes changes based on this review.

data.title: Economical yet Practical RV Park near everything!
data.content: First time parking our Travel Trailer at this park. First impression, the park is large, plenty of parking and secluded areas to BBQ, have family gatherings, parties, ect. The main office personnel were cordial and helpful checking in. The parking spots are plentiful and large. The initial problem we had was that the “full hook-up stations were on the correct side but almost at the left entry corner of the parking spot making it impossible to park near it without your rig sticking out of the parking spot; in other words, to park correctly you will need about 30 feet of water hose, tank drains, electrical, and cable. The other unusual issue is that if you park close to the “hook-ups”, your park bench is on the opposite side of the hook-ups but halfway into the parking spot, so your awning does not open over, or near the park table.Next, there is a walking/running track that runs along the RV park fence (4-feet high) so there is all kinds of traffic (bicycles, rollerblades, running, walking, and everything else) passing by looking into the RV Park. This explains why in their brochure they warn all RVers to lock everything up when not on site; perhaps anyone can jump or use the “open gates on the fence to access the RV Park and no one would even know. Security drives by often and do there best to keep an eye out, but the RV Park is not isolate or has control access. Anyone can just drive or walk right in.There is a building at the center of the RV Park with Men, Woman, Family, RV Park bathroom’s with Key-Code access and the laundry room with six washers and dryers; anyone can just walk in to use them. Now our experience. My wife and I went to use the restrooms during the day and there were several ladies sitting at an outside park table just waiting for someone, in this case my wife, to use the bathrooms so they can gain access (they did not have the code or looked like they were camping there) to use the showers/restrooms. I walked in the “Men’s showers/restroom and bout bathroom stalls were occupied, one guy using the sink, and two using the showers; they looked like they were all related with the ladies outside. I reported it to the desk, they said they would send someone out, no one showed up! The bathrooms are cleaned once a day; hope you get to them early!All in all, it worked for us, but we were constantly concerned with the busy traffic walking by all day long. I would recommend the park management look into upgrading the RV Park security perimeter by increasing the track fence higher and a controlled (keypad) gate at the RV Park entrance to prevent casual walkers/runners or family gathering people to use the RV Park facilities.

data.title: Amazing Natural Wonders
data.content: Topeekeegee Yugnee Park is one of the few natural areas in Broward I had never visited before today. It is located on Sheridan Street, just off I-95. As I was already exploring nearby John Williams Park, I decided to visit this location on the way home. Unlike John Williams Park, this park however greedily charges a fee to enter. They even invested more taxpayer money into constructing a turnpike like toll plaza at the entrance. The public should not be extorted to allow their children to experience nature. This was the only negative. The centerpiece of the park is the huge lake in the center which has a hiking/jogging trail surrounding the perimeter. Wildlife was plentiful. As we hiked we observed moorhens, dragonflies, butterflies, and gray squirrels. Fishing is allowed on the lake. There is also a playground, RV Park, Campground, Water Park, picnic areas under oak tree shade, and areas for sports activities. As we were pressed for time, we did not have a chance to explore the entire park, but hope to return.

data.title: Under Construction
data.content: The north side of the park is in sad shape.  It is undergoing renovations.  It is a “ghost town”.  There are no signs alerting you to the closure of parking lots. New parking lots have been created.  Eventually this might turn out OK but for the time being Tradewinds north is a major disappointment.

data.title: One of the best parks
data.content: I adore this park. It has some of the best trees in South Florida. Many oak trees that are 2-3 feet in diameter, and many trails that run under the canopy spreading several acres. This park also has a sizable cat walk over a lake with a view of birds, turtles, and fish, and of course the occasional gator. This park also frequently has horseback riding for reasonable cost. There is also a small lake for canoeing, a large climbing area for kids, many shelters for family events, and much more. We go to this park once or twice a month, often riding bikes throughout the park. This park is truly a gem in South Florida.

data.title: Maybe the weather spoiled the day
data.content: I was told about this park and I was very eager to go there with my daughter and our cameras.  I read about the animals in the park, trails, the tower, etc, so we were waiting for the day we decided to go. We were there yesterday and had a big time disappointment. It may be the weather was was very cool in the morning and the animals were lazy, , but the fact is that we arrived around 9:30 AM and went first to the Tower.  That was the first frustration as from the top you can only see the nearby trees but the view is not really a breathtaking one.  We expected something more panoramic.  Then we walked around and into a trail but besides trees and vegetation, plus a few visitors, nothing else was there. No iguanas, no birds, no butterflies, so after a few photos taken, we decided to leave and go for lunch.  I think that I may give it another try just in case, but it will be in summer or close to it.

data.title: Nice oasis in an overdeveloped South Florida!
data.content: With so much suburban sprawl in South Florida it's nice to find a park like Tree Tops to be able to  commune with nature. I was there on a quiet weekday afternoon and enjoyed walking up to the wooden viewing tower,it's not so high but did allow for some close up viewing of all the air plants and resurrection ferns growing on the upper tree branches. The lake was quite serene also and I enjoyed seeing some herons apparently courting as they flew reflected over the waters surface. I'm sure that on a busy weekend with so many people and their cars it's not so relaxing but I'm glad that at least we have these small pockets of nature left in South Florida. For anyone interested in more the Everglades are only short drive away from most places in South Florida and that would be a more authentic natural experience!

data.title: Vista View Park Offers Activities for All
data.content: I think Vista View Park is the best"fitness park" in Broward County. If you don't care for a gym membership this outdoor "gym" is the answer.This park was a landfill over 20 years ago. That's why there is a noticeable elevation of about 70 feet. Those looking for a good workout can run or cycle up and down the hill.There are trails on the hill for walking, jogging and running. On the lower elevation, these is a designated trail/path a little under a mile long with about 10 exercise stations. These are sturdy and well-built exercise machines that can be used for upper body and leg exercises. (See photos below.)There are also basketball courts, play areas for kids, pavilions/shelters, 2 fishing decks, specific areas for model airplanes, drones, remote controlled cars and paragliding.There are few trees at this park so you won't find many birds like at Tree Tops Park nearby. However I have seen Cattle Egrets, Great Herons, Burrowing Owls, Northern Mockingbirds, Anhinga and ducks here.On the fourth of July the park is open late allowing you to see fireworks miles away in cities like Fort Lauderdale, Pembroke Pines and Miramar.The park is close to Griffin Road and I-75. Admission is free during the week and $1.50 per person on weekends and holidays.

data.title: What a view!
data.content: Vista View Park is a former garbage dump that has been converted for use as a park. Once at the top, you have a great view of the area. This is one of the highest points in Broward County (perhaps another dump is higher). There are two dump "hills" that make up this park. One of them is open to the public, with a road to the top and parking there as well. The other hill is still fenced off. Maybe one day it will be open to the public. There is a very nice breeze at the top of the hill on almost every day. If you want to relax under a tree enjoying the breeze, well good luck. There aren't that many trees on the top. This is the biggest drawback of this park to me. There just aren't enough trees to provide you with an escape from the sun. There have been more trees planted in recent years, but there are still many areas that (I feel) should have trees.

data.title: Nice peaceful moonlight paddle
data.content: We have our own inflatable SUP's so we brought ours - would end up being the only ones on a SUP but that didn't matter at all. Honestly it made it a little more fun for us I think. The group was led by 3 guides - one lead, and two sweeps. That's important for safety especially since it's dark out and different groups are going at slightly different paces. The house beer is only $1.99 for a 16 oz - and it's a GOOD beer! I recommend arriving early enough to enjoy a beer before heading out. I also recommend bringing a waterproof box or bag for your valuables (keys, money, etc). And a d-clip to secure it. Since we didn't rent (a SUP or kayak) the price was reduced which was good - though it still seemed a tad high for simply showing up with our own stuff (noting the money goes to the guides and liability insurance). Recommended to all - a great Friday evening active 'happy hour.'

value.text: discovered a plaque placed by the Daughters of the American Revolution commemorating this park as the sight of the Colee Hammock Massacre
a spot to take in the waterway

data.title: Gorgeous River View
data.content: A gorgeous 1.1 acre park on the south fork of the New River. It has lovely trees, benches, tables, and a stunning view of the river and the surrounding mansions that line it. There are a few parking spots lining the outside of the park.On my visit while walking around I discovered a plaque placed by the Daughters of the American Revolution commemorating this park as the sight of the Colee Hammock Massacre. I knew about the event and always thought the location was across the river from the Broward Performing Arts Center. I was floored to find the marker and have my years of misconception corrected. William Cooley was one of the first pioneers of the New River Settlement now known as Ft. Lauderale. He became wealthy with an arrowroot plantation and he traded with Seminole and Creek nations nearby. In 1835 the white settlers killed a Creek chief named Alibama and were acquitted. The Creek blamed Cooley for this injustice and when he was away for business in Key West the Creek entered the plantation on January 6, 1836 and killed Cooley's wife, infant son, son, daughter,and a tutor. The house was set on fire. This started the Second Seminole War because the settlers couldn't distinguish between the Seminoles and the Creeks. The eventual outcome was the Indian Removal Act were the native people were forced out west on the Trail of Tears. The remaining Seminoles fled to the inner swampland where they can still be found today. Cooley fled Ft. Lauderdale but lived in Florida until his death.Upon further research I found that the plaque marking the massacre may have been put in the wrong spot as the event actually took place further up the river closer to Sailboat Bend but residents don't want it moved to the correct spot. This is not the only muddling of history at this spot. Residents were confused at the time of the naming of this park in 1934. They originally wanted to honor the Cooley family but there was some confusion about the name. James Louis Colee was also a resident of the New River Settlement but decades after Cooley. He set up a work camp at the site of this park where he worked on the construction of  the Intracoastal Waterway project. Through the years the names of Cooley and Colee have been mixed up. In 1982 the park was officially named Colee Hammock park to reflect James Lois Colee's work camp not the Cooley massacre.Today the park is used as a spot to take in the waterway, fish, and climb the trees. It is also an ideal place to view the Winterfest Boat Parade if you can navigate the lack of parking. I found it an ideal place to reflect on the history of Ft. Lauderdale which has grown from a small trading settlement on the river to a world class city. In the span of roughly 100 years from when it was incorporated into a city in 1911 Ft. Lauderdale has changed yet it was managed to hang onto it's charm in part because of places like this park.

data.content: We visited and stayed at the Bahia Mar Double Tree for three days in October. One very nice feature was that there is a Pedestrian walkway that ran from our hotel to the beach over Seabreeze Ave. This is an amazing Atlantic coast beach. One of the highlights was the picnic area with table and charcoal grills along with several adirondack chairs for just relaxing and taking in the views. They also have a fitness area with stations that is really a cool feature. The beach is clean and  well kept up. The week we were visiting it was rainy and cloudy so the crowds were not big at all and we had easy access to the grills and amenities. We were told that during nice weather that tables and grills went early.

value.text: seen the Atlantic from a warm beach

data.title: So very pretty!
data.content: So very pretty!! I had never seen the Atlantic from a warm beach, just from when I lived in Boston, so of course we had to come here on our way to the Everglades. No reason to come here, it's just where we stopped but I was glad as it's a neat area!It did seem like there were quite a few homeless people and the construction was a pain which is why I didn't leave 5 stars. There weren't any bathrooms that I could find, just porta potties, which were fine for hubby, but I only use those when I run! Looks like there may be restrooms soon, but like I said, due to the construction, there went any (we were there in September).There was ample parking for a decent price, but it wasn't the weekend, or the height of summer, so I'm sure it's different at those times.I loved the showers there...both for your body and for just your feet. That was awesome and a great touch!There is fitness equipment too; when we were there, there were some military members running in cadence  and using the equipment, which was cool to watch.The beach is beautiful and well-maintained, and the water is beautiful and clear. I would definitely love to come back and spend more time here!

data.title: Fun at the Beach
data.content: We were extremely happy with the Beach and state park. The beach was free of seaweed and stuff on the beach unlike the beaches at Key Largo. The water was also a little cooler. The kids had fun wading in the water and floating the waves of the surf. Good place to boogie board and float in an inflatable. We took a cooler and a radio. There were plenty of places down the street to get something to eat. The area is a little more expensive then most. The local market sold good food but it was spending. Ceaser Salad was about $10 not bad for restaurant but spending for a pre-made salad. There was a pretty large bathroom and changing area. There are 2 sets of showers outside to rinse off in.  There is parking near by.

data.title: Great beach!
data.content: You can walk for miles on this clean beach. The sand is soft and there was no seaweed when we visited. The water was very clear, turquoise in close and deeper blue further out. The waves were gentle - it was not possible to surf here or even to really ride the waves.  The beach seems to slope down fairly quickly, do you don't have to go out very far to be able to swim. Lounge chairs are available to rent, but close down shortly after 4:00. There is the beach, then a wide sidewalk, then a road, then shops and restaurants, so you can easily leave the beach and get to food and shopping.  There is paid parking, but it seems as if it might be difficult to find a spot unless you arrive early.

The Beach Park has city bikes to rent for a fee, basketball courts, swings for all ages, and bench parks.   The Park is on the Ocean Front and is open until 2am. data.title: Rising of the Star
data.content: Every year my landlords (who were like family to me) myself and their families would meet at the Fort Lauderdale Beach Park Christmas Eve morning before the sunrise to watch the sunrise and have Christmas Eve breakfast together. We would use the beach grills to cook our bacon and eggs, pull some picnic tables together, sip on mimosas and enjoy each other's company at this beautiful park. It's a beautiful place to watch the sunrise, it's convenient to a parking lot, clean and hardly crowded.  I can't tell you how special this park is to me. You can't be any more blessed starting Christmas Eve out with special family and friends watching the sunrise in a beautiful beach. This tradition went on for years, we called it "The Rising Of The Star, Christmas Eve on the beach"

data.title: perfect for me
data.content: I was on a solo trip in the area, for a concert, and spent 4 hours here the next day. I found an easy parking spot, was able to pay the meter with no problem. It was $2.00 per hour. I was able to put cash into the machine, which was great. The parking was near the bath house. I found a great Aidirondack chair, under a Palm tree, and enjoyed sunning & having a lunch snack. I wanted to go down to the edge of the ocean, but was worried about leaving my belongings. I looked around, and everyone seemed to be decent (couples with little kids, older couples reading, teens just hanging out together & playing music).I didn't feel that anyone would steal my stuff, but since I had my passport, license, credit cards, and a hundred dollars in my bag, I asked an older woman to keep an eye on it. I placed it beside her chair. The sand was clean, the water was crystal clear and great temperature. I didn't get in the ocean, since I was alone, but was wishing I had brought my snorkel mask & someone along. I saw a couple of cruise ships on the horizon. There were fishing boats offshore, too. I would definitely recommend to anyone, young or old. I felt safe and wished I had more time to stay and enjoy the beach.

data.title: Good for locals and tourist alike
data.content: This area is a great area to come to the beach. Many activities take place right along here from Tortuga Music Festival to Friday Night Sound Waves, there is always something going on!! Not quite the boardwalk of Hollywood Beach, but still a nice place to run, walk or ride. During the busy season it can get packed however and you should plan accordingly by getting there early to avoid traffic. Shops along the strip are your typical trinket shops, sometimes they have nice souvenirs there so if you have free time might be worth a stop. The restaurants are really hit or miss, do your research before going. My personal favorites are Casablanca and Coconuts, some of the hotels along there also have good options as well. Make sure when visiting to take picture in front of or sitting on the big beach chair...no visit is complete without that!!!

data.title: Fun and Informative
data.content: We went to Everglades Holiday Park as part of a Princess post-cruise tour.  We had never been on a air boat so this part, especially the speed runs, were a unique experience.  We then saw much quieter sections of the Everglades and were able to view 3 alligators a couple of Iguanas and several large birds, including turkey vultures and egrets; all in their natural habitat.  The boat operator was very informative about the environment and the flora and fauna and spent time circling so that everyone could get good views and take pictures.We then went to the Alligator show.  Our presenter again was informative, very funny and put on a impressive show with the gators.

data.title: Daughter loved the playground
data.content: From out of town... Visited Holiday Park on a day too blustery to be at the beach or pool. It wasn't too windy away from the water, though, so it was honestly a good day for the park.The equipment was perfect, different sizes for different ages, and I appreciated that there was no entry fee to the park since I know many Florida parks require that. However, there was literally NO ONE else there except for a group at the shelter house - it was 11am during the week but I at least expected some other kids. Our 2 year old had a blast, though, so it was a win in our book. It also looks to have many walking/running trails, tennis courts, soccer fields, etc.

data.title: Summer Fun

data.title: LOTS TO DO HERE
data.content: Holiday Park has a lot to offer. It's located only a mile from downtown Ft. Lauderdale and is readily accessible. There are basketball courts and baseball diamonds, a football field and a soccer field. Tennis courts are located on the southern section. A jogging/walking track winds through parts of the park. There are exercise stations along its partially shaded route. A play area for kids, with colorful slides and swings and climbing structures, is available.The War Memorial Auditorium hosts a variety of activities. The Parker Playhouse on the western part of the park features plays and other cultural events.There is a library branch sitting near the northeast corner of the park.

data.title: An Interesting Historic House to Visit
data.content: This historic building, the "Villa Providence," dates from 1924.  It was listed on the National Register of Historic Houses in 2013.  It is a beautiful building, inside and out, of the Italian Renaissance style of architecture.  The history of the Curci family in South Florida is very fascinating.  There are a number of Curci family memorabilia.  I particularly liked the tile work in and above the living room fireplace.Free tours are available the first Saturday of every month, from 11 A.M. to 4 P.M.  There is an excellent film that should be viewed before the tour.

data.title: The bullies of Bougainvilla Drive II
data.content: As my family and I left Lauderdale By the Sea last February, the Town Manager and his staff  told us that they would make the town tennis courts more accessible for all 60 or so of the keyholders. They lied. Instead, the Town Manager, Bud Bentley, personally rewrote the Tennis Court Rules for the specific purpose and with the specific intention of enabling that band of bullies to continue their bullying and bigoted behavior this year. The men still come to the courts before dawn to hold the courts and prevent tennis players who are not part of their group from accessing the courts.  Six times during our stay, I saw waiting players refused entry onto the courts by this group, even though they had monopolized the courts for hours. Instead of limiting court time when its busy, the town decided to let this group play for as long as they want and exclude the other 40 or so families who have rented a court key. On the plus side this year, Broward County Sheriff’s Deputies didn’t even visit once during the 11 times we played. There were no physical threats, although the machine-gun-wielding man from last year still plays here and is still a bully.  The woman who described my grandson in racist terms last still plays here, but managed to keep her mouth shut this year. Although we were on the receiving end of cursing, name-calling and offensive comments every day last year, there was none of that nastiness this year. Obviously, I and family had no difficulty accessing the courts during our two week stay. Although the new rules actually made it easier for us to play, they effectively enable the bully group to keep most other keyholders off the courts from 7a-11a, the prime playing time during the winter in South Florida. I hope that the Town Commissioners read this post, and require that the court rules be rewritten to promote equal access among all keyholders, not just this band of bullies.

data.title: Pickleball Rules!
data.content: The town tennis courts have never been busier...with pickleball now being the primary activity. The old bully crowd still shows up early, but they are far outnumbered by the pickleball people. Pickleball is so popular that the town is planning to convert the two tennis courts into 6 pickleball courts. Now that would be a fitting end to the saga of the Bullies of Bougainvilla Drive!

data.title: I know you can’t control Mother Nature but WOW
data.content: I fell in love with the park the moment I saw it. The entrance is gorgeous, the lake is beautiful and it’s one of the only parks around that has pavilions and a playground close by but it also has swings. I was sold on this park for my daughter’s first birthday. I ended up reserving pavilion #3 with a pretty unobstructed view of the lake. I planned for this birthday for 6 months. I spent way more money than I should have on a 1st birthday (things are expensive in South Florida and I have a BIG family) and my birthday party was pretty much a bust. The wind tunnel that is created in this pavilion, during a cold front, looked like a tornado. Even taping the table cloth down to the picnic tables would not keep them down (they would bubble with air), the beautiful balloon garland and cake backdrop I had planned for to be used with my elaborate cake/dessert table was a bust and had to be taped down to the storage closet at the entrance of the pavilion using duct tape and it still blew off several times damaging the cake. None of the decorations I handmade for the party could be used. None of the decorative balloons could be used. My cousin bought stones at the dollar store just so we could put out the vases on the table but we couldn’t add the flowers because they would have blown over. I know you can’t control Mother Nature but WOW, I can’t be the only person this has happened to and based on a brief conversation I had with a park worker, Management at the park seems aware of this issue. The park needs to invest in wind blockers. Having known this issue in advance, I would have planned the party at this park differently. (for those that say I should have known, NO. All my parties are at parks and this is the first time I have this issue). Other things to consider, the line to get in is ridiculously long and the bathrooms were disgusting. My guests said they were absolutely nasty and overflowing. I'm sure this is due to the soccer tournament that was going on which also took all the parking spaces, even those blocked off for pavilion #3 (I was not made aware these were assigned to our pavilion until the party was over).

data.title: A Nice Boardwalk Walk
data.content: Chapel Trail Nature Preserve is a 460-acre wetland/marsh.  There is no admission charge, and there is a fairly sizeable parking lot.  I think in the nearly 10 times we have been here, there has never been more than four or five cars in the lot.There is a boardwalk, not very long, that meanders through the wetland.  We have only visited in January or February and always been surprised by the lack of waterfowl and wading birds.  It looks like an ideal habitat for them.  The only bird that we have seen regularly, i.e., on every visit we have ever made, is the Purple Swamphen.You can rent canoes on Saturday.  And, along the boardwalk, there are quite a number of signs depicting and with text explaining the flora and fauna of this wetland.

data.title: Peaceful morning on the water
data.content: Who would expect to find an opportunity to quietly commune with nature surrounded by development.  The Chapel Trail Park Nature Preserve has canoes available for rental which allows you to venture out into the local Everglades ponds/wetlands and find a small space of solitude.  If you want to enjoy the peacefulness of the preserve without canoeing, there is a good length of boardwalk which allows you to just relax and enjoy the native birds in flight.  Beware however of the extensive mosquito population.  If you are lucky, you may catch sight of turtles and peacocks which are plentiful in the area as well.

data.title: One Of Our Favorite Places to Visit in South Florida
data.content: I've seen 2 versions of what this is called: a linear park and a linear trail.  I've seen 3 versions of its length: 1.0, 1.1, and 1.5 miles.  A map near the trailhead gives this information:  it's a linear park and 1.5 miles long.This park is for those who walk, bike, jog/run, birdwatch, and skate.  A lot of plants are identified by excellent signs.  But, as you walk through the park, the condition of the signage varies a lot, with some signs being in terrible shape.When we go, we go "to bird."  Since there is water along most of the length of the park, you'll probably see more aquatic birds than terrestrial birds.  This is a terrific oasis smack in the middle of a heavily populated area.

data.title: Good golf, great price, average service
data.content: Played the pines course a while back. The Greg Norman design course plays pretty tough from the tips. Lots of options off the tee with some interesting holes. The greens are in great shape and in my opinion the best thing about the course. Fairways and rough are not in great shape. Pace of play is slow. Summer, twilight rates are cheap and worth the price. Practice facility is not great but dirt cheap, $6 for a large bucket can't be beat.My main complaint about this place though was the poor service I received from the starter and course manager last time I tried to play. They didn't allow a friend and myself on the course as a twosome because "the course was too full," yet, when we got on the course there were a bunch of twosomes. We had no one behind us and caught up to a twosome in front of us, otherwise, very few people on the course (it was 5pm on a Tuesday). Seriously? Total power trip I felt.In general though it's a nice course and for the price it is pretty good golf.

data.title: Peaceful Nature Oasis
data.content: The parks in Weston are some of the nicest and most well-maintained parks in Broward County and the 5 acre Emerald Estates Park is no exception. Located near I-75, Emerald Estates Park is located just outside the gates of the Emerald Estates community in Weston, a neighborhood made of 607 single family homes.Emerald Estates Park has many amenities including a shade covered playground, basketball courts, exercise path, outdoor fitness equipment, lighted tennis courts, picnic shelters and grill. There is even a bike Fixit Repair Station. Dogs are allowed as long as leashed.During my visit I saw a lot of people throughout the park exercising, playing tennis, and at the playground. I walked on the paved fitness trail and tried out the the outdoor exercise equipment. While I worked out I could see all of the birds attracted by the water in the park. At the back of the park is an island filled with wood storks, a large wading bird that is considered threatened in the United States. There were also a lot of cormorants too. Not only is this park a great place to play, exercise, and cook out but it is also a wildlife sanctuary and a fantastic place to bird watch.

Quiet and peaceful, it is a sample of the beauty of Florida with its palm trees, a lake with a nice bridge from which you can see fishes and ducks, a children playground and small kiosks to sit and enjoy what nature has to offer in this place!

data.title: Peace Mound Park
data.content: A lovely, serene park in the city of Weston, Florida. It is the location of an ancient Native American burial ground. There are benches to sit, lots of shade, a pond, ducks...everything you need to relax and unwind. Extremely safe.

data.title: Pretty park
data.content: I'm new to the area so wanted to check out the parks in Weston. This is a cute little park with a great playground for the kids. Next to a pretty lake with a wooden boardwalk and many benches, it is really peaceful.

data.title: Beautiful Park in a beautiful city.
data.content: Such a peaceful park. Lots of Native American history. Lovely place great for bike riding. Very convenient to all vacation villages properties. Also easy walking around a small lake. We even watched kids fishing.

data.content: Very nice park by the lake. With playground for kids and nice sidewalk. And "nice welcoming" ducks ;)

data.title: Enjoy Nature!
data.content: Colohatchee Park is an 8.5 acre community park with a seven acre mangrove preserve. The name of the park came from pioneer William Collier who planted an orange grove in the 1890's. The Seminoles liked his oranges and called him Colo which was a shortened form of Collier. The Seminole word for river was Hatchee so Colohatchee means Collier at the River.The last time I was here, the park was under renovation. It is so nice to see it open. There is a boardwalk from the parking lot that takes you through the mangroves, across the Middle River, and over to the dog park. You have to be registered to use the dog park. There are very few open dog parks any more but it is much safer to have everyone registered.I am so happy to see that Wilton Manors made it a priority to protect this patch of mangrove. The mangroves filter and clean the water, prevent erosion of the coastline, and provide a habitat and refuge to wildlife. The walk is short and it is nice that a boardwalk was put in here but the most important thing this park does is it improves the health of the Middle River.

data.title: Relaxing Oasis
data.content: The crowds on Wilton Drive can wear over time and Island City Park offers a tranquil respite.  There are some typical park like attractions such as a full basketball court outside.  But if you walk toward the back you will find the tributaries to the inter costal waterways.  It is quiet and relaxing.

data.title: Nice parkland area by the river
data.content: Wilton Manors has around 12 parks (and only 12 000 people).  This park is on the edge of the City on there Middle River.  The park has an elevated broad walk built through the mangroves along the river.  Nice for a walk and has some shade for the summer.  Parking adjacent, but watch the times that you have to pay!

data.title: Unexpected breath of fresh air.
data.content: I've passed this park dozens of times. I finally visited and was pleasantly surprised. It's not large but nice for a walk among mangroves and palm trees. There are a couple of pavilions with picnic tables where you can enjoy a nice meal. An added bonus is a boat launch where you can rent kayaks at reasonable rates and take a circular kayaking trip around Wilton Manors.

data.title: Lovely Place to Walk
data.content: This little park is a jem. Right on the South Fork of the Middle River, there is an elevated nature trail that has been built through the mangroves along the river. With covered areas and picnic tables, it is a wonderful place to bring a lunch and dine among the palms. You can also rent a kayak in the park and explore the middle river on your own.
